<HEADLINE> Oklahoma Governor Wants Death Sentence for Bombing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, December 28 (Xinhua) -- Governor Frank Keating of
Oklahoma of the United States said today he wanted Terry Nicols
sentenced to death for his role in the 1995 Oklahoma bombing,
regardless of a jury's mixed verdict earlier this week.
</P>
<P>
The federal jury in Denver, Colorado, found Nicols guilty of
conspiracy and involuntary manslaughter, but not murder. The
penalty phase of the trial is scheduled to begin Monday.
</P>
<P>
The blast of a federal building on April 19, 1995, killed 168
people and injured hundreds more.
</P>
<P>
Keating told "Fox News Sunday" that he believed Nicols should
now be tried on state murder charges, saying Oklahoma could
provide an impartial jury despite being the scene of the tragedy.
</P>
<P>
He supported the state legislature's provision of 1 million
dollars for the state prosecution of Nicols and co-conspirator
Timothy McVeigh, who had already been convicted of murder and
sentenced to death in a federal court earlier this year.
</P>
<P>
Describing the bombing of the Alfred Murrah building as an
extreme case warranting capital punishment, Keating said, "What
worse case can you get? Killing 168 people with premeditation. I
think if capital punishment is not given in this case, it could
not be given in any case." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
