<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-28 16:14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 2 Iranians Get Life Term for Shooting Kuwaiti MP </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, December 28 (Xinhua) -- Two Iranians and a Kuwaiti
man were sentenced to life imprisonment today by a local criminal
court after being convicted of attempted murder of an outspoken
Kuwaiti parliament member in June.
</P>
<P>
The two Iranian brothers named Sayed Mohammed Ardabili, 25, and
Sayed Abdulhadi Arbadili, 19, were punished for their role in the
June 6 shooting of liberal MP Abdullah Al-Neibari and his wife
Ferial Al-Freih.
</P>
<P>
Five suspects, including the two Iranians, were arrested within
24 hours after the assassination took place shortly before night
fall. Al-Neibari was injured by machine-gun fire along with his
wife while driving toward Kuwait City from beach villa near the
Saudi border.
</P>
<P>
The Kuwaiti also sentenced to life imprisonment is identified
as Salman Al-Shamlan, who masterminded the attack.
</P>
<P>
A leading liberal member and head of the Public Fund Protection
Committee in the 50-seat Kuwaiti parliament, al-Neibari is renown
for his fighting against corruption and embezzlement of public
funds.
</P>
<P>
So far no motive was given for the attack, but informed sources
said al-Neibari was about to uncover a defrauding case in which
al-Shamlan was probably involved. A number of cabinet ministers
were then asked by al-Shamlan's committee to face inquiries.
</P>
<P>
During interrogations the suspects mentioned several
high-ranking officials and confessed they "wanted to defend those
ministers and avoid them such an embarrassment."
</P>
<P>
A second Kuwaiti suspect, Adel Mohammad Al-Megemi was sentenced
to a 10 year jail term for his help in the attempt while a third
was acquitted.
</P>
<P>
Life sentence is the most severe punishment by law
in Kuwait except rare execution cases which needs sanction from
state paramount leader the emir. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
