<HEADLINE> Pro-British Guerrillas Claim N.Irish Killing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, December 28 (Xinhua) -- Pro-British guerrillas said
today they killed a former Irish republican prisoner in a gun
attack in Northern Ireland.
</P>
<P>
The man killed was Seamus Dillon, who had served 14 years in
jail for a 1980 murder linked to the province's political and
religious conflict.
</P>
<P>
The attack by the Loyalist Volunteer Force Saturday night was
in reprisal for the killing hours earlier of their leader, Billy
Wright, by Irish republican prisoners inside a top-security jail,
according to reports from Belfast, capital of the province.
</P>
<P>
Wright, a guerrilla leader known as "King Rat," was shot by
members of the Irish National Liberation Army, a breakaway group
from the mainstream Irish Republican Army (IRA). Both groups are
fiercely opposed to British rule in Northern Ireland.
</P>
<P>
The violence, at a time when major guerrilla groups on both
sides of the province's sectarian and political divide are
observing a cease-fire, threatened to plunge Northern Ireland's
peace process into crisis.
</P>
<P>
Britain's Northern Ireland Secretary Mo Mowlam said the
province was living through a "dangerous" phase in its history.
The government would have to respond to events "clearly,
concisely, without over-reacting," she added.
</P>
<P>
She said that she would hold a meeting Monday with her prisons'
minister Adam Ingram, police chiefs and prison officials to
discuss the way forward. 
</P>
</TEXT>
