<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-28 16:29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mubarak Calls for Developing Domestic Tourism </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, December 28 (Xinhua) -- Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak
today called on well-off nationals to help tide over the tourism
depression caused by the November terrorist attack, the Middle
East News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
The well-offs should spend their vacations at home and cut
their travels and spending abroad, Mubarak made the call after
inaugurating an oil field at Wadi al Sahl about 430 kilometers
south of Cairo.
</P>
<P>
"I am certain that the well-to-do Egyptian vacationers can
enjoy the winter and summer attractions of their country better
than any place abroad," he said.
</P>
<P>
"This is the best thing to do to reverse the bad effects of the
Luxor terrorist attack" on tourism of Egypt, he added.
</P>
<P>
Islamic militants relentlessly killed 58 foreign tourists on
November 17 in southern resort Luxor about 500 kilometers south of
Cairo, dealing a crippling blow to Egypt's lucrative tourism
industry during the peak season of the winter.
</P>
<P>
Foreign tourists have reportedly canceled trips to Egypt, and
many countries have warned their nationals against travelling to
Egypt at present.
</P>
<P>
Egypt's Tourism Ministry has said that hotel occupancy rate has
dropped to 18 percent from 70 percent in one month after the
terrorist attack.
</P>
<P>
The Egyptian government is trying to make up for the losses by
targeting three areas, the Arab world, eastern Europe and Latin
America, in addition to encouraging nationals to spend vacations
at home.
</P>
<P>
According to a "100-day program" proposed by the Tourism
Ministry to activate domestic tourism, banks, political parties,
professional unions, sporting clubs, schools and universities have
been suggested to organize trips for their members to places of
interest in Egypt. 
</P>
</TEXT>
