<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe's FM Heads for Zambia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, December 28 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwe's Foreign Minister
Stan Mudenge left Harare Sunday for a three-day visit to Zambia
amid mounting international condemnation of Lusaka's detention of
founding President Kenneth Kaunda on suspicions of involvement in
failed coup.
</P>
<P>
Mudenge however said he was going to attend a joint
Zimbabwe-Zambia ministerial commission discussing the two
countries bilateral agreements and the current political climate
in the region, the Zimbabwe News Agency reported today.
</P>
<P>
Mudenge, accompanied by Mines, Environment and Tourism
Minister Simon Moyo said in an interview at the Harare
International Airport he was also taking to Zambia a special
message to President Fredrick Chiluba from his counterpart Robert
Mugabe.
</P>
<P>
Asked whether the joint commission will look into the arrest
and detention of Kaunda, Mudenge said, "the meeting will look at
all issues affecting the two countries and all our bilateral
agreements."
</P>
<P>
He refused to comment further on the Kaunda case saying he
will issue a statement upon his return from Zambia Wednesday but
sources interviewed later revealed the Kaunda issue was top
priority on Mudenge's agenda.
</P>
<P>
"I am carrying a special message from President Mugabe as the
Organization of African Unity (OAU) chairman. It's a message
from one brother to another brother," said Mudenge as he left in
the Aero Zambia Aircraft at the airport. 
</P>
</TEXT>
