<HEADLINE> Zimbabwean Opposition Party Appeals to Release </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, December 28 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwe's opposition National
Progressive Alliance (NPA) called on Zambian President Fredrick
Chiluba to release former president Kenneth Kaunda detained on
Christmas day on suspicions of involvement in October's coup
attempt.
</P>
<P>
The NPA said on Sunday the Organization of African Unity (OAU)
should send a delegation to Zambia to investigate whether
allegations being levelled against Kaunda, now opposition leader,
were true.
</P>
<P>
NPA President Canciwell Nziramasanga said the OAU should play
an important role in freeing Kaunda who played an important role
in the liberation of most African countries from the reigns of
colonial rule.
</P>
<P>
He said people such as Kaunda, Tanzania's Julius Nyerere and
Ghana's late Kwame Nkrumah were a rare species which should be
treated with Honor rather than humiliation that Kaunda is now
being subjected to.
</P>
<P>
"We are very cross about the arrest of Kaunda and if the OAU
has to maintain law and order in the region it has to move in,"
he said.
</P>
<P>
Kaunda was arrested three days after his return from a
marathon trip abroad ending speculations that he was likely to be
arrested over the October coup bid, staged by junior army
officers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
