<HEADLINE> Zimbabwean Air Controllers'' Strike Causes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, December 28 (Xinhua) -- The International Federation
of Air Traffic Controllers Associations (IFATCA) today said it is
seriously concerned with developments within Zimbabwe's civil
aviation industry following the dismissal by the government on
Wednesday of 67 striking controllers and cadets.
</P>
<P>
IFATCA executive vice-president for Africa and the Middle East
Oliver Farirayi said in a statement the dismissal of the air
traffic controllers and cadets was unjustified especially in the
absence of any serious negotiations to try and meet the demands
of the workers.
</P>
<P>
The controllers were fired after having gone on a work
stoppage following their failure to agree with the government on
the need to revamp their working conditions, machinery, grades
and salaries.
</P>
<P>
IFATCA recommended the dispute be settled through
negotiations, mediation, consultation or arbitration.
</P>
<P>
"For guaranteeing safety, air traffic controllers shall not be
replaced by personnel who do not hold atc licenses, validations
and competency appropriate to the duties that they are expected
to undertake," said Farirayi.
</P>
<P>
He added authorities should not resort to the use of civil
mobilization or "requisition measures for the purpose of ending
or preventing national disputes in air traffic control.
</P>
<P>
He added IFATCA had identified some problems with the air
traffic control system in Zimbabwe which he said could lead to
safety and national security problems.
</P>
<P>
"I would like to ask the authorities to engage in serious
dialogue with the air traffic controllers in order to reach a
mutual agreement. We as an organization aim to promote safety,
efficiency and regularity in international navigation," he said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile the situation at Harare International Airport
remained the same Sunday with most flights leaving long after
their scheduled time. 
</P>
</TEXT>
