<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Britain Set to Slide Down Growth League in EU </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, December 28 (Xinhua) -- Britain is set to lose its
place at the head of the European growth league for the first time
in five years, according to leading economic forecasts.
</P>
<P>
Britain's growth rate has powered ahead of its European
competitors since it left the exchange rate mechanism in 1992.
</P>
<P>
Dresdner Kleinwort Benson forecasts a slowdown in growth in the
UK gross domestic product to 1.8 percent, while Germany should
improve to 2.6 percent, France to 2.7 percent, Italy to 2.6
percent, Portugal to 3.7 percent and Spain to 3.6 percent.
</P>
<P>
It is commonly believed the reasons why Britain will be
overtaken by these countries are its interest rate rises, tax
increases and falling export performance.
</P>
<P>
Michael Saunders, UK economist at Salomon Smith Barney, said
that after "a golden mix" of strong economic growth, falling
unemployment and a successful reduction in the budget deficit in
Britain, "the coming year promises to be very different."
</P>
<P>
Britain's growth rate will fall from 3.5 percent this year to a
consensus estimate of 2.4 percent in 1988, tumbling its place in
the European growth league as low as tenth.
</P>
<P>
Observers here also believe that Britain's performance reversal
may weaken the force of the UK's six-month European Union
presidency and will also fuel the debate on whether Britain should
join the single currency earlier than 2002, as it has indicated.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
