<HEADLINE> Tit-for-Tat Killings in N.Ireland Condemned </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, December 28 (Xinhua) -- Irish Foreign Minister David
Andrews today condemned as "obscenities" the tit-for-tat killings
in Northern Ireland.
</P>
<P>
"The obscenities of recent days may well be designed to
undermine the peace process. They must not be allowed to do so,"
Andrews said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
The shooting of a guerrilla leader and the reprisal killing of
a former prisoner Saturday by splinter groups of major guerrillas
in the British-ruled province demonstrated the opposition to the
peace talks in Northern Ireland, according to reports from Dublin.
</P>
<P>
The full-scale peace talks, beginning last September between
major guerrilla groups on both sides of the province's sectarian
and political divide, aimed at ending nearly 30 years of religious
and political conflict which has also hit the Irish republic.
</P>
<P>
The Irish foreign minister said, "I actively join with other
political leaders in urging calm and restraint, and in emphasizing
that the only way forward is through the dialogue of the talks
process." 
</P>
