<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Netanyahu Makes Major Concessions on State Budget </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, December 28 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Prime Minister
Benjamin Netanyahu has made major concessions to his coalition
partners on the 1998 national budget in an effort to secure their
support, Israel Radio reported today.
</P>
<P>
The report said that Netanyahu held urgent meetings over the
weekend with his coalition partners so that the budget, which
includes a 2.3 billion shekels (about 660 million U.S. dollars)
cut, could be passed in the Knesset (parliament) by its December
31 deadline.
</P>
<P>
The meetings came after some 20 coalition Knesset members had
declared that they oppose all or part of the budget arrangements
bill and refused to vote for the new state budget unless their
demands are met.
</P>
<P>
In the meetings, Netanyahu gave in to Health Minister Yehoshua
Matza demand and agreed to drop the setting up of ministerial
committee that will decide the cut of the health budget. In
addition, 500 million shekels (about 143 million dollars) were
allocated to help cover the 1.5 billion shekels (about 429 million
dollars) deficit in the health care.
</P>
<P>
The National Religious Party has also got a commitment of 275
million shekels (about 79 million dollars) from Netanyahu, 225
million shekels (about 64 million dollars) for education budget
and another 50 million shekels (about 14 million dollars) for
building bypass roads in the territories.
</P>
<P>
The opposition, which is expected to submit its objections
and propose amendments for the arrangements bill to the
Knesset, has charged that Netanyahu has capitulated to coalition
demands that would damage the national interests.
</P>
<P>
And the Labor party said that the concession will cost
billions of shekels and demands that every agreement between
the prime minister and his coalition partners be brought
before the Knesset plenum. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
