<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-28 18:40 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israeli Ministers on Second Tour in West Bank </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, December 28 (Xinhua) -- Israeli cabinet ministers
today took the second inspection tour of the West Bank in a week
to review Israel's security needs ahead of the proposed troop
pullback and permanent talks with the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
The ministers, led by Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu,
surveyed the area by helicopter. They stopped at key hilltop sites
to hear briefings by Infrastructure Minister Ariel Sharon, who
guided today's tour to lobby for support to his redeployment map.
</P>
<P>
Defense Minister Yitzhak Mordechai guided last tour on Tuesday,
proposing the width of the security zones be reduced to be
accepted by the Palestinian National Authority (PNA).
</P>
<P>
However, Sharon said that he demanded the creation of security
zone 20 kilometers wide along the Jordan Valley and another seven
to 10 kilometers wide along the 1949 armistice line, or Green Line.
</P>
<P>
He claimed that his demands were the "minimal" for protecting
Israel's safety.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu agreed with Sharon's view. He also reiterated his
position that no Jewish settlement in the West Bank will not be
dismantled in the overdue second-phase redeployment.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Israel Radio reported today that Netanyahu's
attorney Yitzhak Molcho has told PNA President Yasser Arafat that
Israel was serious in carrying out the pullback in the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
Molcho explained that Netanyahu was having difficulties in
getting the budget for next year passed in the Knesset
(parliament) by the end of the year.
</P>
<P>
Today's tour by the Israeli cabinet is part of the ongoing
preparation for the second-phase troop redeployment in the West
Bank. The United States was urging Israel to produce an agreement
on the percentage of pullback by January 15.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli cabinet had held several sessions to formulate the
pullback in the West Bank and the guidelines for the permanent
talks, but failed to reach an agreement due to division on
security arrangements.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu and Arafat will meet separately with U.S. President
Bill clinton in Washington next month to discuss ways to pushing
forward the stalled peace talks.
</P>
<P>
In early January, U.S. special peace envoy Dennis Ross would
return to the region to continue mediation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
