<HEADLINE> NPA Reaffirms Withdrawal of Dialog </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, December 28 (Xinhua) -- The National Patriotic
Alliance (NPA) reaffirmed here today its withdrwal of the
proposed inter-party dialog.
</P>
<P>
NPA, an umbrella group comprising 12 Zambian opposition
parties, met here this morning to review the recent development
vis-a-vis the inter-party dialog, Acting NPA Chairman M. Lisulo
told a news briefing.
</P>
<P>
He said the situation in the country is not at all conducive
for the holding of the dialog.
</P>
<P>
The continued state of emergency imposed after the October 28
abortive coup does not augur well for the resolution of the
current political impasse, he said.
</P>
<P>
Lisulo condemned the arrests of former president Kenneth
Kaunda and Dean Mung'omba, leader of Zambia Democratic Congress
(ZDC) in connection with the coup.
</P>
<P>
The political parties under the alliance have resolved that no
genuine and meaningful dialog can take place and all the parties
will not take part in the talks unless the state emergency is
lifted forthwith and Kaunda, Mung'omba and all political
detainees be released and all leaders of political parties who
are forced to stay out of the country are free to return and
participate in the dialog without fear of arrest and harassment,
Lisulo said.
</P>
<P>
Micheal Sata, co-chairman of the inter-party talks and
government minister without portfolio said here today that the
proposed inter-party dialog will go ahead as schedule on December
30 and 31.
</P>
<P>
After Kaunda was arrested by police on Thursday a number of
parties announced their withdrawal of the inter-party dialogs
including Kaunda's.
</P>
<P>
At the preliminary meeting held early this month 31 parties
drew an agenda for the inter-party dialog. The agenda includes
most contentious issues like constitution, electoral process and
voters' register and fresh registration.
</P>
<P>
Before Kaunda's arrest 28 parties confirmed their
participation of the dialog, which was originally scheduled early
next month.
</P>
<P>
So far only six parties have confirmed their participation in
the dialog. 
</P>
</TEXT>
