<BODY>
<HEADLINE> One Quit Kenya's Presidential Race at Last Minute </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, December 28 (Xinhua) -- Kenyan presidential candidate
Setphen Omondi Oludhe, the leader of the tiny Economic
Independence Party, announced today the final campaign day that
he quit the race to support President Daniel arap Moi's bid.
</P>
<P>
Moi, 73 and in power for 19 years, is "a wise and able" leader
to be voted for on Monday, the polling day, he was quoted by
local sources as saying in Kisumu, the third-largest city of
Kenya.
</P>
<P>
Oludhe's party, set up late last month, was the youngest party
in the campaign with Moi's 37-year-old ruling Kenya African
National Union the oldest.
</P>
<P>
Oludhe's withdrawal came at the last minute of the campaign
which ended today in a basically peaceful atmosphere nationwide
despite reports on several clashes between youths loyal to
different candidates and leaving three dead, reports reaching
here said.
</P>
<P>
Most rival parties today got their publicity machines to the
top gear to woo voters at last bid.
</P>
<P>
Moi held a final rally in his powerbase Rift Valley Province
today, saying he would list unemployment and corruption his major
priorities if re-elected.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, thousands of supporters of Democratic Party's
presidential candidate Mwai Kibaki attended a rally in central
Nairobi to heed Kibaki's plea for social changes.
</P>
<P>
Most local opinion poll results have indicated that Moi would
head the poll with votes ranging from 40.2 percent to 49.2
percent, almost doubling his closest challenger Kibaki.
</P>
<P>
Electoral Commission Chairman Samuel Kivuitu said earlier that
his commission has completed all arrangements for the elections
and called on all voters to vote on Monday.
</P>
<P>
Kenya will embrace the second multi-party general elections on
the day with a total of 9,031,141 registered voters expected to
cast their ballots to elect one president, 210 parliamentary
members and 2,955 local councillors.
</P>
<P>
Under Kenya's law, the winning presidential candidate must
garner the highest total and collect at least 25 percent of the
votes in at least five of Kenya's eight provinces.
</P>
<P>
As many as 12,754 polling stations around the country are due
to open at 6:00 a.m. tomorrow and close at 6:00 p.m. (0300-1500
GMT).
</P>
<P>
There are 883 candidates from 23 parties running for the
parliamentary seats while 8,446 standing for civic elections.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
