<HEADLINE> Ankara's Reaction to EU Decision Confirms Athens' </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, December 28 (Xinhua) -- Greek Defense Minister Akis
Tsohatzopoulos said today that Turkey's tense reaction to the
European Union (EU) decision not to include her as a candidate
confirmed Greece's long-standing positions.
</P>
<P>
Speaking before departure for a three-day visit to Bosnia and
Albania, Tsohatzopoulos said that the tension and thoughtless
comments with which Turkey reacts to the decision by the EU
regarding her accession confirmed Greece's long-standing position
that the Turkish military leadership had imposed clear conditions
for an aggressive policy towards particular countries.
</P>
<P>
He was referring to an alleged decree signed by Turkish Prime
Minister Mesut Yilmaz which formally defined Greece and Syria as
posing the greatest external threats to Turkey.
</P>
<P>
The issue had caused Greece's concern, he said, but stressed
that the Greek army was ready to deal with any challenge.
</P>
<P>
The EU decided earlier this month not to include Turkey on the
list of nations waiting to join the group, on the grounds of
Ankara's "poor human rights and bad relations with Greece."
</P>
<P>
Turkish President Suleyman Demirel reportedly warned Saturday
that Athens would pay for "blocking Ankara's bid to join the EU."
</P>
<P>
Tension between the two neighboring countries intensified
recently with the mutual expulsion of diplomats and violations of
Greek airspace by Turkish jet fighters.
</P>
<P>
Tsohatzopoulos warned Thursday that Greece's patience with
Turkish belligerence was running out. 
</P>
</TEXT>
