<HEADLINE> S. African Parliament Speaker Meets Chinese </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Cape Town, December 28 (Xinhua) -- South African National
Assembly Speaker Frene Ginwala met visiting Chinese Vice-Premier
and Foreign Minister Qian Qichen here today, expressing welcome
to Qian's visit.
</P>
<P>
Ginwala and Qian agreed that the forthcoming establishment of
diplomatic relations between South Africa and China is a big
event that has been expected by the peoples of the two countries
for a long time.
</P>
<P>
It is also an achievement resulting from joint efforts by the
governments of the two countries, they said.
</P>
<P>
Qian expressed gratitude to Ginwala for her positive
contributions to the promotion of Sino-South African relations
and the establishment of bilateral diplomatic ties.
</P>
<P>
Qian relayed greetings from Qiao Shi, chairman of China's
Standing Committee of the National People's Congress, who invited
Ginwala to visit China as soon as possible.
</P>
<P>
Qian arrived in Johannesburg early in the morning. South
African Foreign Minister Alfred Nzo met him at the Cape Town
airport.
</P>
<P>
During his five-day official visit, Qian will also meet South
African President Nelson Mandela.
</P>
<P>
He is scheduled to have talks with Nzo and sign an official
joint communique over the normalization of bilateral relations on
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Mandela announced in November last year that his country would
sever diplomatic ties with Taiwan and establish comprehensive
diplomatic relations with the People's Republic of China.
</P>
<P>
Qian is scheduled to attend on January 1 the opening ceremony
of the Chinese Embassy in Pretoria, the administrative capital of
South Africa.
</P>
<P>
Accompanying Qian on the visit are his wife Zhou Hanqiong,
Deputy Minister of Foreign Trade and Economic Cooperation Shi
Guangsheng, and Chinese Assistant Foreign Minister Ji Peiding.
</P>
</TEXT>
