<HEADLINE> Jordanian FM Back From Visit to Saudi Arabia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, December 28 (Xinhua) -- Jordan's foreign minister Fayez
Tarawneh said upon his return home from a two-day visit to Saudi
Arabia this evening that Jordanian-Saudi ties were strong.
</P>
<P>
His trip, the second high level visit by a Jordanian official
to Saudi Arabia in six years, was a part of the continued
coordination between the two countries, said Tarawneh.
</P>
<P>
Tarawneh met with Saudi Crown Prince Abdullah Ben Abdul Aziz in
Riyadh during his stay and the two discussed the Middle East peace
process and the outcome of the summit meeting of the Organization
of Islamic Conference held in Tehran, Iran earlier this month,
official Radio Jordan reported.
</P>
<P>
On Saturday, Tarawneh met with Saudi King Fahd and delivered
a verbal message from Hussein to him expressing the desire to
develop bilateral ties.
</P>
<P>
Tarawneh`s visit to Saudi Arabia has been considered "very
important" here in further improving relations with the Gulf
economic giant. Jordan' Crown Prince Hassan paid an official
visit to Saudi Arabia in September this year, during which he met
the Saudi King.
</P>
<P>
Hassan's trip was the first high-level visit by a Jordanian
official to Saudi Arabia after the Gulf war in 1990. Relations
between the two countries were strained after the war as Jordan
refused to support the U.S.-led allied forces against Iraq.
</P>
<P>
Saudi Arabia and other Gulf countries cut off aid to Jordan and
expelled more than 300,000 Jordanian workers during and after
the Gulf War.
</P>
<P>
Relations between Jordan and the Gulf nations improved in 1995
after Jordan distanced itself from Iraq.
</P>
<P>
Saudi Arabia has become Jordan's second largest trade partner
after Iraq. In 1996, Jordan exported 130 million Jordanian dinars
(about 184 million U.S. dollars) worth of goods to Saudi Arabia
compared with 70 million dinars (about 99 million dollars) in
1995, according to official statistics. 
</P>
</TEXT>
