<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-29 15:33 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Turkey Defends Military Actions in Northern Iraq </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, December 29 (Xinhua) -- Turkey said today that its
military operations in northern Iraq were aimed at eliminating the
militants of the outlawed Kurdish Workers' Party (PKK).
</P>
<P>
"If there is a PKK existence in the region, the Turkish
government troops will not completely stop such operations there,"
Turkish Foreign Ministry spokesman Necati Utkan said at a weekly
press briefing.
</P>
<P>
The PKK rebels took advantage of the authority vacuum in
northern Iraq to attack Turkey, posing a serious threat to
Turkey's security, Utkan said.
</P>
<P>
But he assured Turkey's respect for the territorial integrity
of Iraq in the operations.
</P>
<P>
The PKK has sought shelter in northern Iraq and use it to carry
out hit-and-run attacks on targets across the border after the
Iraqi government was rendered ineffective in exerting power in the
region by its defeat in the 1991 Gulf War.
</P>
<P>
Turkey has frequently launched cross-border military incursions
into northern Iraq since 1995.
</P>
<P>
This has prompted strong protests from Iran and Arab countries,
which urged Turkey to respect Iraq's sovereignty and territorial
integrity and withdraw troops immediately.
</P>
<P>
Ankara repeatedly said it did not envisage a permanent military
presence in northern Iraq, adding its troops will pull out as soon
as their objectives are achieved.
</P>
<P>
Turkey sent 50,000 troops into Iraq last May in its largest
cross-border military operation this year to wipe out PKK camps
there. Some units remained in the region after the Turkish
government declared a troop withdrawal.
</P>
<P>
The PKK has been fighting the Turkish government troops since
1984 in an attempt to set up an independent Kurdish state in
southeastern Turkey. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
