<HEADLINE> Turkey Again Downplays Turkish-Israeli-U.S. Maneuvers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, December 29 (Xinhua) -- Turkey today again downplayed
the forthcoming Turkish-Israeli-U.S. joint naval exercises, saying
the exercises are "not directed at any third country" and are open
to military observers in the region.
</P>
<P>
Turkish Foreign Ministry spokesman Necati Utkan told a regular
news briefing that the drill code-named "Reliant Mermaid" is a
routine one aimed at improving search and rescue capabilities of
the three naval forces.
</P>
<P>
"As we said many times, the maneuvers are not directed at any
third country," Utkan said, adding that the countries in the
region should make themselves easy about the matter.
</P>
<P>
He reaffirmed that any countries in the region are welcome to
observe the tripartite naval war games.
</P>
<P>
The Turkish-Israeli-U.S. joint exercises, which had been
postponed for several times, are to be held in the international
waters near the Israeli coast on January 7, 1998.
</P>
<P>
The maneuvers, in the framework of the quickly-expanded
Turkish-Israeli military cooperation since last year, have
triggered sharp criticism from Iran and Arab countries, which
accused Turkey of forming military alliance with the Jewish state.
</P>
<P>
Jordan has agreed to monitor the military exercises as an
observer, Utkan said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
