<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Foreign Investors Hold Less Swedish Stocks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
STOCKHOLM, December 29 (Xinhua)-- Foreign investors, for the
first time in a decade, have started to diminish their total
holdings in the Swedish listed firms.
</P>
<P>
They have sold stocks worth 292 billion Swedish kronor
(about 38.5 billion U.S. dollars), while purchasing only 276
billion Swedish kronor (36.6 billion dollars) by the
end of September in Sweden, statistics from the Sweden's central
bank said Monday.
</P>
<P>
In the same period, Sweden has made net investments in foreign
stocks amounting to 433 billion Swedish kronor (57 billion
dollars), while foreign stocks worth 370 billion Swedish kronor
(49 billion dollars) were sold in this north European nation.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971229.0033 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Premier Li Peng Inspects China Central Television </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 29 (Xinhua) -- Chinese Premier Li Peng
inspected the China Central Television (CCTV) station today,
calling on staff members to take a firm grip on correct public
opinion, and to laud the good and attack the evil.
</P>
<P>
After extending warm regards on the coming new year, Li said
the press had scored indelible impressions in its coverage of such
major events this year as the death of Deng Xiaoping, the 15th
National Congress of the Communist Party of China, Hong Kong's
return to the motherland, Jiang Zemin's visit to the United States
and damming of the Yangtze River at Three Gorges.
</P>
<P>
The premier toured a number of studios at the TV station and
said he was pleased to see that the station is providing colorful
and welcome programs to the public.
</P>
<P>
With trial broadcasting in 1958, CCTV has grown into one of the
largest television stations in the world, boasting eight channels
and airing 139 hours of varied programs daily. 
</P>
</TEXT>
