<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 1997: Epoch-making Events to Decide China's Future (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 29 (Xinhua) -- For both the enormous grief
and joy it brought to the country, the year 1997 may well define
the history of China, especially the history of development since
its reforms and opening-up to the outside in the late 1970s.
</P>
<P>
If any doubt had been cast over China's prospects during the
post-Deng period, that doubt disappeared with a series of special
events that occurred in 1997. The year could foretell where China
will go.
</P>
<P>
With such major events on the schedule as the Hong Kong
handover, the convocation of the 15th National Congress of the
Communist Party of China (CPC), and the damming of both the
Yangtze and Yellow rivers, the year was expected to be different.
</P>
<P>
However, the death of Deng Xiaoping, chief architect of China's
reforms and opening-up, added another special touch to the year.
</P>
<P>
Despite the fact that Deng had been retired several years
before his death, that the third generation of CPC collective
leadership had matured, and that the 18-year-long reforms and
opening-up had laid a solid foundation for further development of
the country, the outside world had voiced concerns about what
image would emerge in the post-Deng era. The country started
reform and opening-up under the guidance of Deng, and had entered
a critical stage. Skeptics were still pessimistic about China's
future after Deng.
</P>
<P>
It was this special background that would undoubtedly determine
the decisive importance of the subsequent series of events
afterwards.
</P>
<P>
Although some predicted political upheavals based on some
superficial analyses, China's political situation has remained
stable. On the contrary, the ruling CPC successfully maintained a
stable political situation and accomplished the trans-century
leadership changes in an orderly fashion as the end of the century
approached.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
