<DOCNO> XIE19971229.0041 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's First Blood Donation Law to be Implemented </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 29 (Xinhua) -- China's first law on blood
donations, passed here today at the 29th session of the Standing
Committee of the Eighth National People's Congress (NPC), China's
top legislative body, will be effective Oct. 1, 1998.
</P>
<P>
The law, designed to guarantee the safe use of blood,
emphasizes that voluntarily donated blood can only be used in
clinical practice and must not be sold.
</P>
<P>
The law stipulates: "The state advocates healthy citizens aged
between 18 and 55 to donate blood voluntarily, and encourages
personnel of organs of the state, soldiers on active service, and
students in colleges and universities to take the lead in doing
so."
</P>
<P>
To guarantee the safety of the blood donors and users, the law
sets rigid rules on the establishment, duties, and operation of
the blood donation centers which collect and provide plasma for
clinical use.
</P>
<P>
The law prohibits blood donation centers from excessive and
frequent drawing of blood from donors. And the voluntarily donated
blood cannot be sold to blood-products enterprises.
</P>
<P>
According to the law, anyone or any medical institution who
illegally collects blood, sells voluntarily donated blood, or
unlawfully organizes others to sell blood will be imposed a fine
of under 100,000 yuan (12,000 U.S. dollars), in addition to
confiscation of the illicit income. Those violating the law also
will face criminal responsibilities.
</P>
<P>
Shan Ouqi, an official from the Department of Medical
Administration under the Ministry of Health, said that to meet the
demand of the clinical use of blood, the state encourages the
patients not in critical condition to store their own blood before
operations. The patients' relatives, friends, colleagues and the
whole society are encouraged to help patients.
</P>
<P>
Shan said the state will develop and popularize new
technologies for the clinical use of blood, and medical
institutions are prohibited from wasting blood.
</P>
<P>
Some of the details of the law have yet to be formulated, Shan
said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
