<HEADLINE> China to Safeguard Computer Networks Connected to Internet (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 29 (Xinhua) -- A special administrative
regulation on the protection and management of computer
information networks connected to the Internet will be
promulgated and become operational starting this Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Zhu Entao, assistant minister of Public Security, made his
remarks here today at a press conference, adding that the
regulation, approved by the State Council on Dec. 11, will govern
institutions and individuals engaged in computer information
networks hooked up to the Internet.
</P>
<P>
Statistics from the Internet Information Center of China show
that China had more than 49,000 host computers and 250,000
personal computers connected to the Internet at the end of
October, as well as some 620,000 subscribers to the Internet.
</P>
<P>
Zhu said that the regulation, formulated in accordance with
several state laws and regulations, aims to enhance the protection
and management of computer information networks connected to the
Internet to safeguard national security and social stability.
</P>
<P>
Zhu pointed out that the implementation of the regulation is
bound to help the national police force to crack down on
computer-related crimes and safeguard the legitimate rights and
interests of both institutions and individuals engaged in the
field.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971229.0045 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China to Safeguard Computer Networks Connected to Internet (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Since China began its opening-up drive in 1978, computer
information networks established by various regions, walks of life
and government departments have become an indispensable means and
tools in the management of state affairs, economic construction,
national defence construction and frontiers of science and
technology.
</P>
<P>
The assistant minister pointed out that the connection of
China's computer networks to the Internet in 1994 has tremendously
promoted the country's cultural and scientific exchanges with the
rest of the world.
</P>
<P>
"But the connection has also brought about some security
problems, including manufacturing and publicizing harmful
information, as well as leaking state secrets through the
Internet," Zhu said.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that as China accelerates the growth of the
information industry, wide applications of computer networks in
various spheres have made it a pillar of social development.
</P>
<P>
"Hence, the safe and effective management of computer
information networks is a prerequisite for the smooth
implementation of the country's modernization drive," Zhu
said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
