<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Legislator Calls For Reducing Beijing's Air Pollution </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 29 (Xinhua)-- A member of the Standing
Committee of the National People's Congress, China's top
legislature, called for effective measures to reduce air pollution
in the capital.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the legislature's plenary meeting today, Huang
Yicheng said that Beijing's air contains too many harmful
elements.
</P>
<P>
In 1996 the amount of suspended particles, sulphur dioxide and
nitrogen oxide in Beijing's air far exceeded state limits and the
standards set by the World Health Organization.
</P>
<P>
"Beijing has become one of the 10 most-polluted cities in the
world monitored by the United Nations Environment Program," Huang
said.
</P>
<P>
A nationwide air-monitoring project conducting the week of
Nov. 21-27 by the National Environmental Protection Agency shows
that Beijing has the nation's worst air pollution followed by
Guangzhou in south China and Chongqing in southwest China.
</P>
<P>
Huang said the deteriorating air quality in Beijing is caused
mainly by auto emissions and coal use. Each year the city burns
nearly 30 million tons of coal without proper facilities for
desulphurization and dehydrogenation during combustion.
</P>
<P>
Although Beijing has promoted the use of lead-free gasoline, it
has not acted to reduce pollutants in auto exhaust.
</P>
<P>
To improve air quality, Beijing should use less coal and
develop other energy sources such as natural gas, electricity and
nuclear energy, Huang said.
</P>
<P>
"It should readjust its industrial structure and relocate some
heavy energy-consuming industries to other places," he said.
</P>
<P>
Also, Beijing should give priority to developing public
transportation modes that use electricity and natural gas as
fuels. Automobiles without devices for purifying emissions should
be banned in the city, Huang added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
