<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Adopts Earthquake-Safety Law </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 29 (Xinhua) -- The Standing Committee of the
National People's Congress (NPC), China's top legislature, today
adopted a law on earthquake safety and disaster relief.
</P>
<P>
The law, aimed at reducing losses caused by earthquakes and
protecting people's lives and property, will become effective
March 1.
</P>
<P>
The newly adopted law stipulates that earthquake safety and
disaster relief should focus on prevention efforts combined with
rescue work. The work will be listed in the national economic
growth and social development plan.
</P>
<P>
The law also encourages scientific research of methods to
reduce earthquake damages.
</P>
<P>
The law also requires the central and local governments to
draft plans on earthquake monitoring and prediction, and the
central government will unify the administration of earthquake
monitoring stations all over the country.
</P>
<P>
According to the law, all new buildings or remodeling projects
must meet national earthquake-safety requirements. Major projects
such as nuclear power stations and nuclear installations must pass
an appraisal of earthquake safety.
</P>
<P>
Central and local governments are also required to make rescue
plans in the event of a devastating earthquake. The emergency
plans cover traffic administration, unified distribution of food
and medicine as well as ways of solving of housing and
communications problems.
</P>
<P>
Members of the NPC's Education, Science, Culture and Public
Health Committee said adopting the law is necessary because of
China's vulnerability to earthquakes.
</P>
<P>
Adopting the law will reduce losses caused by earthquakes,
protect people's lives and guarantee the smooth economic growth of
the country, they said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
