<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, December 29 (Xinhua) -- Iran has strongly attacked
Turkey for its insistence on conducting military exercises with
Israel and the United States in the eastern Mediterranean next
month, Iranian newspaper Jomhuri Eslami reported today.
</P>
<P>
The paper quoted Iranian Foreign Ministry spokesman Mahmoud
Mohammadi as saying Sunday that "Iran has repeatedly voiced its
deep concern and regret over the expansion of Israeli influence on
the soils of its neighbors."
</P>
<P>
The spokesman said that during the eighth Islamic summit held
in Tehran on December 9-11, Islamic leaders have warned of the
threats posed by the Israeli government in the region and asked
Turkey to reconsider its military ties with Israel.
</P>
<P>
"We ask Turkey to pay serious attention to the interests of the
Islamic world," the spokesman said, adding that the main goal of
the Israeli government in such ties with Turkey was to divide it
from other Muslim countries.
</P>
<P>
Mohammadi warned that boosting military cooperation and holding
join maneuvers with Israel would lead to instability in the region.
</P>
<P>
Iran can not remain indifferent toward such developments in
the region, he added.
</P>
<P>
The tripartite military exercises among Israel, Turkey and the
United States are scheduled to be held in the eastern
Mediterranean on January 5-9 in accordance with a military
cooperation accord signed between Israel and Turkey in February,
1996.
</P>
<P>
Iran and most Arab countries have expressed great concern over
the military cooperation between Israel and Turkey and the eighth
Islamic summit adopted a resolution calling for reconsideration
of military cooperation between Islamic countries and Israel.
</P>
<P>
However, Turkey and Israel argued that their military
cooperation was not targeted at any other country. 
</P>
