<DOCNO> XIE19971229.0061 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HK Fares Well in Regional Financial Crisis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, December 29 (Xinhua) -- Hong Kong's financial
markets, operating with good management, have "fared well" in the
regional financial crisis, Anthony Neoh, chairman of the
Securities and Futures Commission, said on Monday.
</P>
<P>
Local markets set five records in the year, "the highest
turnover ever in the Stock Exchange and Futures Exchange, the
highest volatility since 1987, the highest diversity of products
ever to rank Asia's most diverse market, the highest number of
authorized funds and fund managers and the highest number of
registrants ever", said Neoh in a review of 1997.
</P>
<P>
Compared to the days of the market crashdown in October 1987,
the Stock Exchange traded 9 times the turnover and the Futures
Exchange traded 4 times the number of contracts.
</P>
<P>
There were 250,000 trades pending settlement in October 1987 in
the Stock Exchange which was one of the reasons for its closure
for four days while default in a massive scale in the Futures
Exchange prompting the introduction of the lifeboat loan.
</P>
<P>
But things improved a lot in October 1997. "The markets
continued to open and worked perfectly.... All settlements went
through and there was no backlog," Neoh noted.
</P>
<P>
During the year, the regulating body has been focusing on
directions such as maintenance of fair and orderly markets,
improvement of financial soundness and internal controls of firms,
maintenance and improvement of standards, and investor education,
he said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
