<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Uganda, Tanzania Promote Mutual Trade </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, December 29 (Xinhua) -- Uganda and Tanzania are
trying to promote mutual trade between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
Tanzania Harbors Authority (THA) is setting up a special cargo
handling center at Dar-es-Salaam Port for Kampala-bound goods
from earlier next year, The New Vision quoted a market report
released by the Uganda Export Promotion Board (UEPB) as reporting
today.
</P>
<P>
"All Uganda-bound transit cargo will be cleared within 24
hours from the time of arrival at Dar-es-Salaam Port ready for
loading and an onward journey to Kampala," said the UEPB report.
</P>
<P>
Ports Dar-es-Salaam of Tanzania and Mombasa of Kenya are the
main competitors for the transport market in Uganda and central
Africa.
</P>
<P>
Local trade communities here complained their goods via
Mombasa enjoyed no preferences comparing to the goods destined
for Rwanda, Burundi and Democratic Congo.
</P>
<P>
The report is a part of a market study aimed at increasing
bilateral trade between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
Uganda's exports to Tanzania are averaged 2.2 million U.S.
Dollars in 1993-1994 and 1995-1996 financial years while its
imports from Tanzania are averaged at 8 million U.S. Dollars
during the two years, official figures indicated.
</P>
<P>
It is possible to balance the trades by increasing the export
from Uganda to Tanzania.
</P>
<P>
Industrial production in Uganda is on rise in nearly all
sectors of manufacturing and not fully absorbed by local market,
and it is needed to find a market for the products, the report
said.
</P>
<P>
According to the report, northern Tanzania with a population
of seven million people, some 25 percent of the whole population
of the country, is a great potential market for Ugandan products
like soap, plastics, mattresses, hoes, iron, steel items and
bicycles.
</P>
<P>
The main barriers for Ugandan products to enter Tanzanian
market are uncompetitive prices, the report said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
