<HEADLINE> Singaporeans Not Allowed to Buy More Than 2 KG of </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, December 29 (Xinhua) -- Singaporeans shopping in
Johor, Malaysia, are prohibited from buying more than 2 kilograms
of any controlled item like flour, cooking oil, sugar and milk,
effective Monday, according to the Malaysian national news agency
Bernama.
</P>
<P>
Johor's proximity to Singapore and the depreciating ringgit
have made the items cheaper and conducive for Singaporean
shoppers.
</P>
<P>
The restriction is to ensure that local people would have
sufficient supply of the commodities in preparation of the double
festive season -- Muslims' new year and the Chinese New Year,
Johor State Environment and Consumer Affairs Committee Chairman
Chua Soi Lek was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
Cooperation of the customs authorities, supermarket and shop
owners as well as Singaporeans themselves were being sought to
ensure compliance with the ruling, the official said.
</P>
<P>
The customs with the assistance of the state enforcement
officers will keep checks on Singaporeans leaving the state at the
Johor Causeway and the Malaysia-Singapore Second Link, he said.
</P>
<P>
The official said that anyone flouting the ruling could be
charged under the Control of Supplies (Export Prohibitions)
Regulations 1996, which provides for a fine of maximum 15,000
ringgit (3,856 U.S. dollars) or two years jail, or both and the
goods confiscated.  
</P>
</TEXT>
