<HEADLINE> China's Onshore Oil Production Up </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 29 (Xinhua) -- China expects to pump 143.2
million tons of onshore crude oil this year, or 1.8 million tons
more than last year's figure, showing the sharpest annual rise
since 1990.
</P>
<P>
According to the China National Petroleum Corp.(CNPC), the
country has made notable progress in oil and gas exploration this
year, discovering 10 complete oil and gas fields each with
reserves above 100 million tons equivalent.
</P>
<P>
In total, the country's additional proven and probable oil and
gas reserves amounted to 1.8 billion tons equivalent this year,
creating the highest record over the past 12 years.
</P>
<P>
Through implementation of the policy of "stabilizing oil output
in east China and developing oil production in west China", the
country has succeeded in slowing down oil decline in the aging oil
fields in the east, and speeding up oil development in the west.
</P>
<P>
The Tarim, Changqing, Karamay and Qinghai oilfields have
recorded unprecedented rise in oil production.  
</P>
</TEXT>
