<DOCNO> XIE19971229.0068 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Africa's Current Account Deficit to Widen </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, December 29 (Xinhua) -- South Africa's current
account deficit is set to widen next year, increasing the
country's reliance on large foreign capital inflows to sustain
even a mediocre growth rate of about two percent, the Business
Day newspaper reported today.
</P>
<P>
Also adding to the country's need for foreign capital will be
the rise in foreign debt that is due next year.
</P>
<P>
Although most of it will be rolled over, some of it will
require new capital commitments from foreign creditors and
investors.
</P>
<P>
Economists are forecasting a current account deficit next year
of nine billion to 12 billion Rand (1.9 to 2.5 billion U.S.
dollars), from about 7 billion Rand (1.45 billion dollars) this
year.
</P>
<P>
The current account, which measures the non-capital flow of
transactions between countries, serves to monitor a country's
foreign trade.
</P>
<P>
Without compensating capital inflows, the deficit will eat
into the country's already threadbare foreign exchange reserves,
said the paper.
</P>
<P>
Despite ambitious plans of the South African government to
attract foreign investment, investors are wary about pumping
money into the country.
</P>
<P>
As for November this year, South Africa netted only 2.3
billion dollars of foreign capital, with a large portion confined
to buying existing assets.
</P>
<P>
According to the Reserve Bank's latest Quarterly Bulletin,
foreign debt with maturity of less than one year amounted to nine
billion Rand in December, while other foreign debts falling due
next year totaled 2.9 billion Rand (600 million dollars). These
debts would have to be rolled over or new commitments would have
to be made to avoid dipping into the foreign exchange reserves.
</P>
<P>
Economists believe that the balance of payments is set to
deteriorate even though economic growth will cool down.
</P>
<P>
Slow economic growth usually boosts the balance of payments
because, as domestic demand cools, companies usually turn to
export markets and the demand for imports abates.
</P>
<P>
However, the sharp drop in the gold price and the Asian
financial crisis are expected to put a damper on South African
exports, while trade liberalization should keep imports high.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971229.0069 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> OAU Welcomes Cairo Agreement Reached by Somali </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, December 29 (Xinhua) -- The Organization of
African Unity (OAU) has welcomed the peace agreement reached by
Somali political leaders in Cairo, Egypt last week, according to
an OAU press release available here today.
</P>
<P>
In the release, OAU Secretary General Salim Ahmed Salim
expressed the hope that all the Somali political leaders would
join together in pursuit of the peace process so as to bring
about a political settlement with the support of the
international community.
</P>
<P>
Salim also looked forward to a new era of peace and national
reconciliation which will bring an end to the suffering and agony
the people of Somalia have been going through over the last seven
years.
</P>
<P>
He paid warm tribute to the Egyptian government for the
sustained efforts it deployed in support of the peace process in
Somalia particularly in facilitating the recent concluded Cairo
Somali talks.
</P>
<P>
After almost six weeks of negotiations in Cairo, Somali
faction leaders, including the two big factions of Hussein
Mohammed Aideed and Ali Mahdi Mohammed, agreed last week on
measures to end seven years of fragmentation under rival
warlords. 
</P>
