<HEADLINE> Vietnam Selects New Communist Party Chief </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, December ((28)) (Xinhua) -- Le Kha Phieu, 66, was
elected general secretary of the Communist Party of Vietnam (CPV)
at its 4th plenary session last Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Do Muoi, 81, former general secretary of the CPV, now acts as a
consultant of the CPV central committee.
</P>
<P>
Le Kha Phieu, born in Thanh Hoa Province in northern Vietnam on
December 27, 1931, joined in Vietnam's revolution when he was only
15 and withstood all trials and tribulations in the anti-French
and anti-American struggles.
</P>
<P>
He joined the CPV in 1949 and Vietnam People's Armed Forces
(VPAF) in May 1950. After 1978, he acted as the political
commissar of the 9th Military Zone until 1988 when he was promoted
to deputy director of the general political department of the VPAF.
</P>
<P>
At the 7th Congress of the CPV held in 1991, Le Kha Phieu was
elected a member of the central committee of the CPV and then
became director of the general political department of the the VPAF.
</P>
<P>
He was elected secretary of the secretariat of the CPV central
committee in 1992 and a member of the political bureau of the CPV
central committee in January 1994.
</P>
<P>
At the 8th Congress of the CPV held in 1996, Le Kha Phieu
became a standing member of the political bureau of the CPV
central committee and took charge of routine duties of the bureau.
</P>
<P>
Le Kha Phieu noted in his articles, carried by Vietnamese
newspapers recently, that the CPV will adhere to the policies of
comprehensive reform.
</P>
<P>
He said, "the policies of reform are in keeping with not only
objective principles but also the aspirations of the Vietnamese
people."
</P>
<P>
Vietnam is facing both opportunities and challenges now, he
said. The CPV is determined to build a peaceful, independent,
unified, democratic and prosperous Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
"In a bid to continue pushing forward the cause of the reform
and speeding up the industrialization and modernization of the
country, we must further implement the policies and guidelines
made by the CPV and properly handle the problems emerging from new
circumstances," he noted.
</P>
<P>
He also stressed the need to flexibly apply Marxism-Leninism
according to the objective reality in Vietnam. 
</P>
</TEXT>
