<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Low Inflation Raises Hopes for S. African Economy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, December 29 (Xinhua) -- The surprise fall in
South Africa's consumer inflation rate to 6.8 percent in November
has raised hopes for a more rapid improvement in the economy next
year, local economists said.
</P>
<P>
The average inflation rate for 1998 could fall to 5.5 percent,
driven by lower interest rates and slower demand in the economy,
"The Citizen" newspaper reported today after surveying seven
South African economists.
</P>
<P>
The average inflation rate this year was estimated at slightly
above 8 percent, the report said.
</P>
<P>
The experts polled provided a range of forecasts for 1998's
inflation between 5.5 percent and 7.25 percent.
</P>
<P>
The economists said interest rates, which have a weighting of
14 percent in the consumer price index, are widely expected to be
reduced by two or even three percentage points in the first half
of next year.
</P>
<P>
The Reserve Bank lowered its lending rate to commercial banks
by one percentage point, from 17 to 16 percent in October.
</P>
<P>
They expect two cuts in interest rates with prime at 17.25
percent by the end of the year, down from the current 19.25
percent, while long term rates could be reduced to 12.5 to 14.1
percent.
</P>
<P>
The economists predicted a gross domestic product growth
between 1.5 and 2.7 percent for 1998, compared with the 1.7
percent growth expected for this year.
</P>
<P>
Exports growth was predicted to be between two percent and 4.5
percent with imports rising at a slow rate of between 1.5 percent
and 2.7 percent.
</P>
<P>
Economist disagree on the country's future current account
deficit with forecasts varying widely from five billion Rand
(1.03 billion U.S. Dollars) to 11.6 billion Rand (2.39 billion
Dollars), but it is believed that the deficit is set to widen
next year.
</P>
<P>
The current account deficit this year stood at about seven
billion Rand (1.45 billion Dollars).
</P>
<P>
According to predictions, the South African currency would
further depreciate. Predictions on the exchange rate against the
U.S. Dollar range from 4.97 to 5.3 Rand, up from the current 4.85
Rand.
</P>
<P>
Private consumption expenditure could grow by 1.4 to 2.5
percent in real terms next year, while government consumption
expenditure vary from zero to 3.3 percent real growth, the
economists said.
</P>
<P>
The gross domestic fixed investment could grow by 2 to 4.5
percent, with a likely poor start and pick-up later next year.
</P>
</TEXT>
