<HEADLINE> Kenyans Cast Ballots in Peace, No Violence Seen </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
(by Xu Jianmei, Wang Jinyu)
NAIROBI, December 29 (Xinhua) -- Nearly 10 million registered
Kenyan voters this morning queued up orderly and peacefully for
casting their ballots to choose the fittest person who will lead
the eastern African country into the next century.
</P>
<P>
"No reports on violence have arrived so far. The voting is
being carried out very peacefully," Electoral Commission Public
Relations Officer Mahamed Koor told Xinhua at noon.
</P>
<P>
He said some people who attempted to take the opportunities
for stealing here and there have been detained in various parts
of the country, claiming no arrests today can be related to the
polling.
</P>
<P>
Unconfirmed local reports said radical Islamic preacher Sheikh
Khalid Balala and a senior member of the National Development
Party were arrested by the police.
</P>
<P>
Queues of up to 400 voters can be seen in many polling
stations in capital Nairobi where all main downtown streets are
almost left empty and silent.
</P>
<P>
All polling stations in the country were scheduled to open at 6:00
a.m. and continue for 12 hours. However, complaints came
following many of them were delayed to open, leaving voters
waiting for a long time.
</P>
<P>
The polling station located in Highridge Primary School,
Westlands, Nairobi, saw the first vote cast there at 10:45 a.m.
although many voters came there four to five hours before.
</P>
<P>
Social Democratic Party's presidential hopeful Charity Ngilu,
cast her ballots around 8:00 o'clock after waiting in the dark
for over 90 minutes, also complainted the postpone,
the Kenya Television Network (KTN) reported.
</P>
<P>
"The Electoral Commission is ill-prepared," she said. Ngilu is
one of the first two women in Kenya to vie for the top seat and
takes the third place in most opinion polls before the elections.
</P>
<P>
But Koor said that the delay is normal, citing the
preparation of ballot papers and transport of 27,000 monitors to
a total of 12,754 polling stations as main reasons.
</P>
<P>
"All the polling stations will close in the evening at the
exact time when they opened in the morning," said Koor, adding
that many Kenyans have predicted the delay and would turn out and
vote in the evening.
</P>
<P>
It is Kenya's second multi-party general elections since
its independence in 1963, with a total of 9,031,141 registered
voters expected to cast their ballots to elect one president, 210
parliamentary members and 2,955 local councillors.
</P>
<P>
Under Kenya's law, the winning presidential candidate must
garner the highest total and collect at least 25 percent of the
votes in at least five of Kenya's eight provinces.
</P>
<P>
Opinion polls before today's election showed that President
Daniel arap Moi, 73 and in power for 19 years, would head the
poll with votes ranging from 40.2 percent to 49.2 percent, almost
doubling his closest challenger Mwai Kibaki, the Democratic Party
Chairman.
</P>
<P>
But most people interviewed by Xinhua in Nairobi today,
including dozens of rich Asian-origin people, said they want a
change in the leadership, citing corruption, economic slump, weak
state of infrastructure, administration with low efficiency as key
reasons.
</P>
<P>
Presidential candidate Setphen Omondi Oludhe, the leader of
the tiny Economic Independence Party, announced his withdrawal on
Sunday at the last minute, reducing runners in the country's most
crowded presidential race to 14. He said he will support Moi.
</P>
<P>
There are 883 candidates from 23 parties running for the
parliamentary seats while 8,446 standing for civic elections.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
