<HEADLINE> S. Africa's Truth Body Denies Report of Intl </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, December 29 (Xinhua) -- South Africa's Truth and
Reconciliation Commission (TRC) has denied a newspaper report
that some South Africans would be brought to an international
court for their part in apartheid, The Citizen newspaper said
today.
</P>
<P>
The TRC had no part in any plan to establish an international
criminal court where people could be tried for crimes against
humanity, war crimes and genocide, TRC spokesperson Christelle
Terreblanche said Sunday.
</P>
<P>
She said the TRC's mandate is only to compile a report with
recommendations to the South African parliament and the truth
body is not part of any proposed international legal process.
</P>
<P>
A Sunday Afrikaans newspaper, Rapport, said that there is a
growing suspicion that some South Africans will be charged in an
international court because they had protected or promoted the
apartheid policy.
</P>
<P>
The paper said a committee of the United Nations in New York
had already formulated laws for the criminal court's jurisdiction
and that the court could be established as early as the middle of
1998.
</P>
<P>
According to Rapport, General Constand Viljoen, former Head of
the Defense Force, and other defense officials who planned or
executed cross-border operations had for some time been aware of
the possibility that they could be called to account by
"international tribunals."
</P>
<P>
"They will probably start with cross-border operations, for
which you cannot ask the TRC for amnesty, because it did not
happen on South African territory," Rapport quoted Viljoen as
saying in an interview.
</P>
<P>
He said the TRC exercise is aimed at obtaining as much
information as possible for hearing before an international
criminal court, or perhaps an African tribunal, when the TRC's
term expires.
</P>
<P>
Rapport said judge of South African Constitutional Court,
Richard Goldstone, and Graca Machel, President Nelson Mandela's
companion, are among those who are promoting the idea of an
international criminal court.
</P>
<P>
Other well-known sponsors of the court include former UN
secretary-general Boutros Boutros-Ghali and former U.S. president
Jimmy Carter and others. 
</P>
</TEXT>
