<HEADLINE> Water-supply Project Quenches Thirsty of Yan'an Residents </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
XI'AN, December 29 (Xinhua) -- A new water-supply project has
been able to supply drinking water to 200,000 urban dwellers in
Yan'an, known as the cradle of the Chinese revolution in the 1930s
and 1940s.
</P>
<P>
The project diverted water from Wangyao Reservoir 52 kilometers
north to Yan'an, a city in northwest China's Shaanxi Province. It
can supply 50,000 tons of drinking water daily to meet the demand
not only of urban residents but also 16,600 rural residents and
their livestock.
</P>
<P>
Yan'an has been well-known in China because it served as the
headquarters of the CPC-led (Communist Party of China) struggles
against the Kuomintang regime and invading Japanese troops in the
1930s and 1940s.
</P>
<P>
However, it had to battle serious shortages of water in recent
years due to arid weather and growing demands for water in the
wake of rapid economic development. 
</P>
