<DOCNO> XIE19971229.0082 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's First Law on Prices (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 29 (Xinhua) -- China's first law on prices
was passed after examinations and revisions at the 29th meeting of
the Standing Committee of the Eighth National People's Congress
(NPC) which closed here today.
</P>
<P>
The law's purpose is to standardize pricing, to give full play
to the role of prices in rationally distributing resources,
stablize market prices and protect the legitimate interests and
rights of consumers and dealers. The law also is meant to promote
the healthy development of a socialist market economy.
</P>
<P>
The law, to become effective on May 1, is suitable for all
pricing in the country including commodities and services.
</P>
<P>
Legislators and legal experts who have attended the
examinations and revisions of the price law all agreed that
pricing has an important bearing on economic development, the
people's standard of living and social stability.
</P>
<P>
The law has great significance in terms of creating a sound
market environment for rational pricing and equal competition, and
protection of consumers' and businessmen's interests and rights,
legislators said.
</P>
<P>
The Price Law embodies China's successful experiences in
reforms and the opening-up drive in the last two decades, and
reflects the demands of a socialist market economy.
</P>
<P>
The law stipulates that the state will put into effect and
gradually perfect a mechanism which will allow the market to
regulate prices under macro-economic control. Pricing must conform
to the law of value, and the prices of most commodities and
services will be regulated by the market. However, the prices for
a few kinds of commodities and services will be guided or set by
the government, the law states.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971229.0083 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's First Law on Prices (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
According to the law, dealers have the right to set prices
within the scope regulated by the market or guided by the
state. They also have the right to report and charge activities
infringing their rights to set prices according to law.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the law also requires traders to sell and
purchase commodities or provide services with marked prices, and
forbids them to charge fees without marked prices.
</P>
<P>
The law states that activities which involve dumping goods with
prices lower than costs, driving up prices, cheating,
discrimination and raising or pushing down prices deliberately all
will be considered illegal activities.
</P>
<P>
The law stipulates that the government, if necessary, can set
prices or guide pricing for commodities and services including
those which have an important bearing on national economic
development and people's livelihood, commodities which have scarce
resources, and important public utilities and public welfare
services.
</P>
<P>
The law says that it is an important target of the state's
macro-economic policy to stablize the overall level of market
price.
</P>
<P>
To protect the interests of farmers and their initiative for
production, the law also stipulates that the government has the
right to introduce protective prices when the market rates for
grain and other important farm products are too low.
</P>
<P>
According to the law, consumer organizations, workers'
organizations for supervising prices, neighborhood and villagers
committees and individual consumers have the right to supervise
pricing. Media organizations also have the right to supervise
related activities.
</P>
<P>
The law also has concrete stipulations on punishment and the
legal liabilities of dealers.
</P>
<P>
Interest rates, exchange rates, premium rates, stocks and
futures prices are not subject to the law. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971229.0084 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Africa's Black Opposition to Make Peace with </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, December 29 (Xinhua) -- South Africa's largest
black opposition, the Inkatha Freedom Party (IFP), has vowed to
accelerate its efforts to make peace with ruling African National
Congress (ANC), according to a local press report today.
</P>
<P>
The "Business Day" newspaper quoted IFP National Chairman and
Kwazulu-Natal Premier Ben Ngubane as saying at a rally in
northern Kwazulu-Natal on Sunday that the peace process would be
expedited in the new year with the aim of bringing security to
all the citizens of South Africa.
</P>
<P>
Kwazulu-Natal, where the IFP is based, is the only province in
the hands of the party.
</P>
<P>
Ngubane said a true democracy is characterized by "harmonious
cooperation" between people of different political persuasions.
</P>
<P>
"We are steadily marching towards that goal," he added.
</P>
<P>
Hinting that the quest for peace would not end the contest for
power between the ANC and IFP, he said the IFP's membership had
the "awesome responsibility" of ensuring the party's victory in
the 1999 elections in Kwazulu-Natal with an increased majority.
</P>
<P>
The IFP won 50.3 percent of the vote in the 1994 provincial
elections. A drop in support would force it to enter into a
coalition provincial government with one of the opposition
parties, most likely the ANC, observers said.
</P>
<P>
Ngubane said the IFP also needed to improve its performance in
other provinces. This, observers said, was the key to the ANC's
offering IFP leader and Home Affairs Minister Mangosuthu
Buthelezi a position befitting his stature in a post-1999
government at national level.
</P>
<P>
Ngubane said the IFP needed to increase its membership,
revitalize its branches and identify issues around which the
party could mobilize support in a peaceful manner.
</P>
<P>
Buthelezi also said at a rally earlier in the month that his
party wanted to be at peace with the ANC.
</P>
<P>
"We can no longer afford divisions and we must realize that in
the end, if our country is to succeed, we must stand together,
failing which we are doomed to fall together," he said.
</P>
<P>
The two parties were involved in a bitter struggle for
political power in the 1980s and early 1990s and violent clashes
between them left more than 20,000 deaths.
</P>
<P>
Before and during ANC's 50th national conference held in
Mafikeng, North-West Province, between December 16 and 20, ANC
President Nelson Mandela reached out an olive branch to the IFP.
</P>
<P>
In a TV interview on the eve of the conference, Mandela said
the two black-based parties should merge.
</P>
<P>
However, the IFP said it has not been officially approached by
the ANC on this matter and hinted that a merger is not likely in
the near future. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
