<DOCNO> XIE19971229.0087 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Northwest China Province Builds Resource Centers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
XINING, December 29 (Xinhua) -- Resource-rich Qinghai Province
in northwest China has built seven major industrial centers over
the past five years in a bid to expand the local economy.
</P>
<P>
The centers involve such industries as animal by-products,
potash fertilizer, petroleum, electricity, ferro-silicon,
salt-based chemicals and traditional Chinese medicinal herbs,
according to today's "People's Daily."
</P>
<P>
Qinghai is one of China's major areas of animal husbandry.
Residents there used to depend on its vast grasslands
which cover 96 percent of the province's land mass of more than
720,000 square kilometers.
</P>
<P>
However, harsh natural conditions and unprofitable livestock
farming had failed to provide enough money to meet local
residents' basic needs.
</P>
<P>
The province started building industrial centers in the
1990s. This year Qinghai registered an all-time high industrial
output of 10 billion yuan (1.25 billion U.S. dollars), which
nearly doubled that of agriculture and animal husbandry.
</P>
<P>
This indicates that Qinghai, whose topography is typical of
plateau and high mountains, has succeeded in optimizing its
economic structure and relying on resources-oriented industries.
</P>
<P>
During the past several years Qinghai has established a dozen
animal by-product processing firms and annual turnover from yak
wool alone now stands at 380 million yuan.
</P>
<P>
To beef up the "lifeline" industries, Qinghai has been active
in introducing shareholding and asset-restructuring mechanisms
into related enterprises. So far, the province's seven listed
companies have raised 1.5 billion yuan (18.8 million
U.S.dollars).
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that Qinghai has 139 foreign-funded companies,
2,349 private enterprises and 15 enterprise groups. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
