<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bank Projects Slower Growth for Hong Kong Next Year </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, December 29 (Xinhua) -- Hong Kong's economy will
grow more slowly in 1998, with the city experiencing cost
adjustment to restore its competitiveness, the Hongkong and
Shanghai Banking Corporation (HongkongBank) predicted Monday.
</P>
<P>
External trade is expected to expand only moderately, being
adversely affected by the recent Asian financial turmoil, while
domestic demand will be dampened by falling assets prices and
higher interests rates, the bank's economic advisor George Leung
said.
</P>
<P>
Overall, real Gross Domestic Demand will rise by 4.0 percent in
1998, compared with the bank's 5.4 percent projection for 1997,
he said.
</P>
<P>
The bank's December issue of Economic Report described Hong
Kong's economic prospects for 1998 as "a year of adjustment" under
the linked exchange rate system.
</P>
<P>
The bank observed that the Special Administrative Region (SAR)
has for the most part "fared well" in the midst of the Asian
financial upheaval. "Despite criticism over the linked exchange
rate system, Hong Kong would have suffered an even more drastic
slowdown as a result of destabilizing speculation if the system
was not in play," said the report.
</P>
<P>
Due to the anticipated slowdown in domestic demand, inflation
will edge lower to 5.3 percent in 1998, from the forecast 5.9
percent for 1997.
</P>
<P>
However, the continued fall in inflation, partly the result of
an adjustment in asset prices, will be "instrumental" in reviving
Hong Kong's competitive edge, the bank said, as the previous
increase in domestic factor costs has already cut into Hong Kong's
overall competitiveness.
</P>
<P>
The slowdown brought forth by the Asian currency disturbances
is "actually expediting the process of restoring the SAR's
competitive position", the bank said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
