<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Macao Airport Reports Sustained Growth </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MACAO, December 29 (Xinhua) -- The Macao International Airport
has seen a sustained business growth both in passenger flow and
the amount of cargo shipment over the past two years following its
commercial operation.
</P>
<P>
Figures released by the airport management company show that
between January and November this year, the airport transported
1.80 million passengers, up 76 percent from the same period in
1996.
</P>
<P>
Cargo shipment in the period reached 40,000 tons, up 142
percent from the same period last year.
</P>
<P>
So far, the airport has opened 16 air routes to destinations
mostly in China's inland and Southeast Asia. It has transported a
total of over three million passengers and 60,000 tons of cargo.
</P>
<P>
Experts say that growth rate was not surprising for a new
airport. The increase of passengers was mainly the result of the
quasi-direct flight across the Taiwan Straits. More and more
Taiwanese travelers to the mainland opt for the route as it is
more convenient and efficient than other choices.
</P>
<P>
Apart from Taiwanese passengers who account for 56 percent of
all, other passengers are from China's inland and the southeast
Asian nations.
</P>
<P>
Joao Moreira, chairman of the board of directors of the Macao
Airport Company, said he was satisfied with what the airport had
achieved so far.
</P>
<P>
He is optimistic about the future business growth of the
airport, predicting a passenger growth of about 10 percent in 1998
and a cargo shipment growth of more than 20 percent.
</P>
<P>
He said if proper efforts are made, the passenger flow of the
airport will not be affected much by the financial crisis in
Southeast Asia, the possible direct air traffic across the Taiwan
Straits in the near future and the upcoming opening of Hong Kong's
new airport.
</P>
<P>
While the financial turmoil in Southeast Asia will cut the
number of travelers to Macao, Moreira said that his airport plans
to make more efforts of promotion in North America, Japan and
Australia, hoping to attract more passengers from those regions.
</P>
<P>
"If direct air traffic across the Taiwan Straits is not
realized until the year 2000, it will have little influence to
Macao airport," he said. "By the time of the direct air traffic,
we would have cultivated other markets and reduced the proportion
of Taiwanese passengers."
</P>
<P>
The most important thing is, he said, "we have to open more
market sources in the period."
</P>
<P>
In addition, he said Macao Airport is capable of meeting the
challenge of Hong Kong's new Chek Lap Kok Airport after it begins
operation next April.
</P>
<P>
The cost of using Hong Kong new airport will be higher than
that of using Macao airport, he said, adding that the new airport
is way too far from the downtown area while it is just one hour
from Macao airport to central Hong Kong. 
</P>
</TEXT>
