<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, December 29 (Xinhua) -- Share prices declined
sharply in thin trading on the Singapore market as the benchmark
Straits Times Industrials Index fell by 34.58 points to close at
1517.94 points on Monday.
</P>
<P>
Dealers said that blue chips suffered selling pressure on fears
of higher interest rates, as local major banks, the Overseas
Chinese Banking Corporation and the United Overseas Bank,
announced that they were raising their prime lending rates by half
a percentage points.
</P>
<P>
Concerns over an economic slowdown in 1998 as brokerage houses
downgraded their forecasts for Singapore's Gross Domestic Product
also fueled selling, they said.
</P>
<P>
Total market volume was thin at merely 76.52 million units,
valued at 112.79 million Singapore dollars (67.54 million US
dollars). Declines outnumbered advances by 193 to 97, while 317
other counters remained unchanged.
</P>
<P>
MBf Capital was the most actively traded counter as it
registered a turnover of 3.78 million units. It was followed by
Inno-Pacific which had 3.32 million shares traded. GPE was next
with 2.67 million units changed hands.
</P>
<P>
Jurong Engineering Warrant0207 and the Singapore Press Holdings
Foreign shared the top spot on the gainers' list as each of them
rose by 20 cents to finish at 70 cents and 20.8 Singapore dollars
respectively. Local beverage and food maker F&AMP;N increased by 15
cents to end at 7.15 Singapore dollars, while TAC was 10.5 cents
higher at 38.5 US cents.
</P>
<P>
On the downside, Creative 50 was the biggest loser as it
declined by 90 cents to end at 32.3 Singapore dollars. ICT fell by
55 cents to close at 80 Hong Kong cents. Shell lost 46 cents to
finish at 2.6 Singapore dollars.  
</P>
