<HEADLINE> Gas Gathering Plants to Tap Nigerian Resources </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, December 29 (Xinhua) -- Three foreign oil companies
operating in Nigeria are expected to begin work on their gas gathering
plants next year to ensure supply of feedgas for Nigeria's 3.8 billion
U.S. Dollars liquefied natural gas (LNG) project.
</P>
<P>
The companies, namely Shell, Elf and Agip, will provide the LNG
plant now under construction in Bonny, south Nigeria's Rivers State,
with about 850 million standard cubic feet per day of gas as
feedstock, the Daily Times reported today.
</P>
<P>
The three firms, which are present in Nigeria as partners of oil
joint ventures with the Nigerian government are also equity holders in
the LNG project, with Shell having 25.6 percent, Elf 15 percent and
Agip 10.4 percent.
</P>
<P>
The Nigerian government controls 49 percent equity interest in the
project through the Nigerian National Petroleum Corporation.
</P>
<P>
As the government is expected to release its 1998 budget before the
end of this year, the companies have alerted for adverse effect of
budget cut, saying that low funding may stall the feedgas project.
</P>
<P>
Nigeria boasts abundant natural gas resources, estimated at 15-30
billion cubic meters. However most of the gas flow has long been
flaring.
</P>
<P>
To make use of the gas resources, Nigeria has decided to build
several gas projects. One of it went into operation in May this year
and its LNG has been exported to the United States.  
</P>
</TEXT>
