<HEADLINE> S. Korean Parliament Passes Bills on Financial Reforms </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, December 29 (Xinhua) -- South Korea's National Assembly
this afternoon passed 19 bills on financial reforms.
</P>
<P>
This was achieved after a long dispute over a planned financial
supervisory agency governing banks, securities houses and
insurance companies.
</P>
<P>
The lawmakers finally reached an agreement to place the giant
financial supervisory agency under the control of the Prime
Minister's Office.
</P>
<P>
They also agreed to allow the tax authorities to gain access to
individual financial transaction data only when they need to
investigate a suspected tax evader.
</P>
<P>
They allowed the government to circulate unregistered
long-term bonds worth five trillion won (about 3.5 billion
U. S. dollars) for a limited period to help cash-starved
businesses procure funds more easily.
</P>
<P>
In response to the IMF-dictated bail-out terms on financial
sector restructuring, the reform package will allow less strict
restrictions on mergers and acquisitions of insolvent financial
institutions.
</P>
<P>
South Korea has been in serious financial crisis caused by the
failure of a group of conglomerates and bad loans of financial
institutions.
</P>
<P>
The nation has signed an agreement with the International
Monetary Fund for a bail-out loan valued at 57 billion
U.S. dollars with tough conditions.
</P>
<P>
Under the agreement, South Korea has to restructure its
economy, open its financial market and cut its budget while it
has to face massive layoffs. 
</P>
</TEXT>
