<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Malaysian Finance Minister Denies Squeeze on Credit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, December 29 (Xinhua) -- Malaysian Deputy Prime
Minister Anwar Ibrahim Monday dispelled notions that the
government is maintaining a credit squeeze, saying it was only
slowing irrational credit growth which had soared surpassing even
the national economic growth.
</P>
<P>
Loans grew at 30 percent last year, an unrealistic rate as
against the national economic growth rate of eight percent, Anwar,
who is also Finance Minister, said in the northern state of Pulau
Pinang, the Malaysian national news agency Bernama reported.
</P>
<P>
As such, the government would scale down credit growth to 25
percent by year end, 20 percent during the first quarter of the
new year and subsequently to 15 percent by the end of 1998, he
said while addressing members of the Pulau Pinang joint chambers
of commerce.
</P>
<P>
As of last November, he said, domestic loans grew by 84.9
billion ringgit (21.88 billion U.S. dollars), or nearly 26
percent, to 417.7 billion ringgit (107.65 billion U.S. dollars)
from 332.8 billion ringgit (85.77 billion U.S. dollars) in the
previous year.
</P>
<P>
Anwar said a 15 percent credit growth was more realistic as
against the projected four percent national economic growth for
next year.
</P>
<P>
Anwar was confident that Malaysia could get out of the present
economic predicament in 1998.
</P>
<P>
The Malaysian government is encouraging loans to productive
sectors and has allowed banks to give priority credit according to
recent official guidelines.
</P>
<P>
"The government is encouraging loans for export and high-tech
sectors and selected services to back economic activities," Anwar
was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
He added "Loans are only discouraged for two sectors, the
property sector and the unproductive one such as for consumer
spending...but loans for low and medium-cost homes up to 150,000
ringgit are not affected."
</P>
<P>
The report said that on margin calls, the finance minister
said, banks should be allowed flexibility in managing loans
issued.  
</P>
</TEXT>
