<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australia's Unemployment Rate to Move Down </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, December 29 (Xinhua) -- Australian Employment
Minister David Kemp said Monday that anecdotal evidence suggested
the Australian economy was on track for budgeted jobs growth, but
the unemployment rate would not move as quickly because of the
many hidden unemployed.
</P>
<P>
Kemp was commenting on a study which found a bright outlook for
an acceleration in jobs, particularly in the retail, tourism and
building sectors.
</P>
<P>
"All this confirms the fact that Australia is entering a period
of sustained jobs growth that was indicated by the Australian
Bureau of Statistics figures," Kemp told reporters.
</P>
<P>
While the latest anecdotal evidence supported the budget
forecast of 8.0 percent unemployment by the middle of next year,
it was not enough to warrant a downward revision of the
unemployment rate, Kemp said.
</P>
<P>
"We are very confident that by the middle of next year we will
reach the budget forecast of eight percent unemployment. Jobs
growth also ought to make the budget forecast of 2.5 percent," he
said.
</P>
<P>
However, Kemp warned that an acceleration in jobs growth was
unlikely to be mirrored by a fall in the unemployment rate, as the
rate did not represent the hidden unemployed who could move into
the labor force as fortunes improved.
</P>
<P>
"Unemployment as a rate will fall more slowly than the jobs
growth, because there is a large pool of hidden unemployed out
there," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
