<DOCNO> XIE19971229.0104 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Few S.African Policeman Disciplined for Prison </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, December 29 (Xinhua) -- The South African Police
Service (SAPS) has disciplined only 27 policemen implicated in escapes
from police or court cells although the majority of escapes took place
in its jurisdiction, The Star newspaper reported today.
</P>
<P>
More than 900 prisoners have escaped from police custody this year,
most of them from charge offices and during normal working hours, the
paper said.
</P>
<P>
Unlike the Correctional Services Department, which suspends an
employee suspected of involvement in an escape, the SAPS waits until a
formal charge has been laid against a staffer.
</P>
<P>
A survey of 118 police stations in Gauteng Province conducted
by The Star revealed that few policemen are disciplined as a
result of escapes.
</P>
<P>
According to the survey, out of a total of 906 escapes from Gauteng
police stations this year, departmental action was taken against only
28 police members, of whom 27 were suspended.
</P>
<P>
More awaiting-trial prisoners escaped from police station charge
offices than from court and holding cells. And a large proportion of
escapes, as high as 50 percent in certain stations, occurred during
normal office hours between 8 a.m. and 4 p.m.
</P>
<P>
As part of the concerted clampdown on prison escapes, the Justice
Department is considering the possibility of hearing separate cases
against already convicted felons in prison. It is also considering
hearing bail applications inside prison for prisoners already in
custody.
</P>
<P>
The newspaper said there was a contrast between the Correctional
Services Department and the SAPS in the approach to the question.
</P>
<P>
The introduction of measures in August by the Correctional Services
allowing for the suspension of an official immediately after an
escape, and pending the outcome of an investigation, resulted in a
drastic decline in escapes from prisons in the last quarter of 1997.
</P>
<P>
More than 50 officials have been suspended since the directive was
issued and escapes from prisons have declined from about 110 a month
prior to August to 86 a month in the three months after August.
</P>
<P>
However, police spokesmen are cagey about the introduction of
similar measures in the SAPS. The sheer number of police stations and
the impact the suspensions would have on the already depleted manpower
of the SAPS would be "too severe to contemplate."
</P>
<P>
The nation was shocked when six of the country's most dangerous men
escaped from a Pretoria prison at the beginning of the month. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
