<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Vietnam Marks Anniversary of Victory Over U.S. Blitz </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, December 29 (Xinhua) -- Vietnam marked the 25th
anniversary of the country's victory over the U.S. B-52 blitz on
Vietnamese capital of Hanoi in December 1972, an editorial of
national daily Nhan Dan reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
In an attempt to force Vietnam to sign a U.S.-dictated treaty
on the on-going war in the country, the U.S. forces started the
12-day-long attack on December 18, 1972.
</P>
<P>
The editorial said that the U.S. scheme failed with 30 raiders
including 23 B-52s and F-111s brought down over Hanoi by the
Vietnamese armed forces during the 12-day attack.
</P>
<P>
With the victory, Vietnam forced the United States to
eventually sign an agreement in Paris, which recognized Vietnam's
independence and sovereignty and ended the U.S. involvement in the
Vietnam war, the article said.
</P>
<P>
The report stressed that the people's ardent patriotism, the
spirit of national independence, sovereignty, wisdom and
creativeness, which had led to Vietnam's victory, should be fully
utilized in the fight against poverty and backwardness, and in the
cause for national industrialization and modernization. 
</P>
</TEXT>
