<HEADLINE> China, Russia Sign Nuclear Power Contract </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 29 (Xinhua) -- China and Russia signed a
general contract here today for co-building a major nuclear power
plant in the port city of Lianyungang in east China's Jiangsu
province.
</P>
<P>
Chinese premier Li Peng and vice-premier Li Lanqing attended
the signing ceremony, who also met a delegation from Russia headed
by first Vice Prime Minister Boris Nemtsov and minister of atomic
energy V.N. Mikhailov.
</P>
<P>
The first-phase project of the nuclear power plant includes the
installation of two water-pressure nuclear power generating units
made in Russia.
</P>
<P>
Under the contract, the Russian side will be in charge of
designing, supply and trial operation of the whole set of nuclear
equipments as well as personnel training. The earthwork will be
undertaken by the Chinese side.
</P>
<P>
The pouring of concrete for the project will start in June of
1999, and its first and second generating units, with a combined
generating capacity of two million kilowatts, will be put into
operation in 2004 and 2005, respectively.
</P>
<P>
It is believed that the electricity to be generated by the
nuclear power plant will play a significant role in boosting
economic development in east China.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, it will help to improve the structure of energy
resources in Jiangsu province. 
</P>
</TEXT>
