<HEADLINE> Nigeria to Trim Civil Service </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, December 29 (Xinhua) -- No fewer than 10,000 civil servants
at the federal level may lose their jobs next year due to a massive
retrenchment exercise planned by the nigerian government for early
next month.
</P>
<P>
A government white paper on the exercise, billed to commence
anytime from the second week of January, will soon be out, the
Nigerian Tribune reported today.
</P>
<P>
The retrenchment exercise is in compliance with the Head of
State's recent directive that the federal civil service be trimmed or
else he would not approve the new recommended salary structure.
</P>
<P>
According to the newspaper, committees have been set up in federal
government ministries to compile names of those who may fall into the
categories of people whose service are no longer required.
</P>
<P>
Some of the criteria for determining such categories of people
include those who are in the habit of coming late to work, those who
have been confirmed medically unfit, and people whose productivity are
considered to be on the decline.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that those to be trimmed mainly include
cleaners, drivers and messengers, as the government also wants to
reduce its huge wage bill.
</P>
<P>
In the last two years, the federal civil service has been carrying
out mass lay-off of workers.  
</P>
