<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> News Analysis: Fundamental Changes Expected in Blood Donation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 29 (Xinhua) -- China's first law on voluntary
blood donation, passed by the top legislative body here today,
marks a fundamental change in the blood donation work which has
been practiced for more than a dozen years.
</P>
<P>
The 29th session of the Standing Committee of the Eighth
National People's Congress(NPC), closed here today, announced that
the blood donation law will become effective starting from October
1, 1998. The law stipulates that the state implements the system
of voluntary blood donation.
</P>
<P>
Minister of Public Health Chen Minzhang said that the "Blood
Donation Law" will be a milestone in the country's blood donation
work, and marks an important progress in the promotion of the
country's socialist cultural and ethical progress.
</P>
<P>
China first introduced compulsory blood donation among its
citizens in 1978. However, the work in this regard remains at a
low level due to weak publicity and lack of legal administration.
</P>
<P>
Shan Ouqi, an official in charge of blood management from the
Ministry of Public Health(MPH), disclosed that at present the
blood volume for clinical use stands at some 800 tons annually in
the country, with 4 million blood donators, with about 50 percent
professional blood sellers.
</P>
<P>
She said, driven by economic gains, some of the sellers provide
blood too frequently, leading to the decrease in the blood quality.
</P>
<P>
A survey by the MPH shows that the incidence of positive
reaction in the test on the HBsAg (hepatitis B surface antigen)
stands at 30-90 percent in the blood provided by professional
blood sellers.
</P>
<P>
Shan continued, the paid blood donation has twisted the spirit
of humanitarianism, and runs contrary to the traditional virtues
of the Chinese nation featuring unity, fraternal love and mutual
aid.
</P>
<P>
Shan said, introduction of voluntary blood donation system and
banning on blood selling will basically stop the occurrences of
the above-mentioned phenomenon.
</P>
<P>
According to Shan, 11 people's congresses and governments at
provincial and municipal levels in the country have passed local
blood donation regulations, with some of their successful
experiences included in the just-passed blood donation law.
</P>
<P>
At present, the MPH has established a well-equipped management
organ and contingent for blood collection and supply, and has set
up 347 stations for blood collection, storage, separation and
transportation across the country.
</P>
<P>
By November this year, there had been 72 cities in the country
which have more than 10,000 voluntary blood donators each.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971229.0133 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-29 </DATE_TIME>
