<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hunan Province Reports Rapid Economic Growth </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHANGSHA, December 29 (Xinhua) -- The gross domestic product
(GDP) of Hunan, an inland province in central China is projected
to top 300 billion yuan (37.5 billion U.S. dollars) this year,
according to a provincial government report.
</P>
<P>
Hunan's GDP -- the value of goods and services produced -- has
grown at an average annual rate of 11 percent since 1993.
</P>
<P>
The growth rate of agricultural output is projected at 8
percent this year, according to the report. The traditionally
agricultural province has expanded its acreage planted to quality
rice to 133,000 hectares.
</P>
<P>
So far, the province has set up 64 centers for producing and
processing grain, cotton, cooking oil and sugar, with the output
of these products accounting for more than 70 percent of the
province's total, the report stated.
</P>
<P>
The report also said that Hunan's industrial output grew by 11
percent this year, reaching 191.9 billion yuan (23,98 billion
U.S. dollars). Its steel output will reach 2.4 million tons this
year, an all-time provincial record.
</P>
<P>
Some company groups producing electric wire and cables, iron,
steel and paper have broken into the international market, because
of the adjusted economic structure.
</P>
<P>
In a move to open wider to the outside world, the province
has increased funding for infrastructure construction and five
key industries -- machinery, food, metallurgy, building
materials and textiles, according to the report.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the province has achieved a balance between revenue
and expenditure for five consecutive years. This year's revenue is
estimated at 25.2 billion yuan (3.15 billion U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
The retail price index has dropped to one percent this year, and
consumer price index to three percent, said the report.
</P>
<P>
The province has invested 268.3 billion yuan in fixed assets in
the last five years, at an annual growth rate of 26
percent. Thirty-eight key projects -- such as the Changsha and
Xiangtan power plants, Shimen-Changsha Railway and Chenglingji
Port -- have been completed or are being undertaken.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the province has handled imports and exports
totaling 14.3 billion U.S. dollars over the past five years. It
has actually used 4.6 billion U.S. dollars in overseas investment
in that period.
</P>
<P>
With rapid economic development, the province has helped
900,000 farmers rise above the poverty line this year. The per
capita income of urban and rural residents is expected to reach
5,358 and 2,000 yuan, respectively, both up five percent from last
year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
