<DOCNO> XIE19971229.0136 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> More Farmers in Shandong Join Old-Age Pension System </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JINAN, December 29 (Xinhua) -- Farmers in east China's
Shangdong Province will no longer depend exclusively on their
children for their later years, thanks to an old-age pension
insurance system that has been set up in rural areas.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that 17 million farmers in Shangdong, an
economic powerhouse in China, have joined the rural pension plan
which started in 1991, accounting for 50 percent of the total
eligible for social insurance. About 2.3 billion yuan has been
accumulated in the pension fund.
</P>
<P>
The province has 59 million farmers, 68 percent of the
province's total population. And most of people who are 60 or
older live in rural areas.
</P>
<P>
The rural pension system is part of the social security network
China is building to minimize the side effects of its booming
market-oriented economy.
</P>
<P>
A certain amount of pension insurance money should be paid by
individuals when they are still working. They will improve their
chances of having a better life by getting pension.
</P>
<P>
Payment by individual farmers usually accounts for half of the
total insurance premiums and the rest is paid by villages where
they live and township-run enterprises.
</P>
<P>
The province plans to set up a unified, comprehensive
rural pension insurance system in the next three years, said Zhang
Ruifeng, vice-governor in charge of rural insurance.
</P>
<P>
So far, 30 provinces, municipalities and autonomous regions
have introduced an old-age pension insurance system in rural
areas. Altogether, 82 million farmers have joined the insurance
plan and the amount in the fund has topped 12 billion yuan. About
400,000 farmers have drawn the pension. 
</P>
</TEXT>
