<HEADLINE> New Policy to Boost Tanzania's Mineral Production </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, December 29 (Xinhua) -- Tanzania is expected to
implement a new mineral policy, aiming at increasing mineral
production from two percent of the annual Gross Domestic Product
(GDP) to 10 percent.
</P>
<P>
Under the new policy, Tanzania will introduce reforms which
will guarantee foreign exchange repatriation of profits,
favorable tax and regulatory treatment for mining investors,
leaving the door open for private investments, the East African
newspaper quoted officials from the Ministry of Energy and
Minerals as reporting today.
</P>
<P>
The policy will also strengthen institutional, environmental
and legal aspects, said the report.
</P>
<P>
The officials from the Ministry said the policy has already
been endorsed by the cabinet and will be launched by Minister
Abdallah Kigoda.
</P>
<P>
The policy's more important responsibilities include the
opening up of the sector to allow complete private ownership of
mineral prospecting. This will shift the role of the government
from that of owning and operating mines to that of stimulating
private mining investment and providing support of investors.
</P>
<P>
"The private sector will play the role of being the principal
vehicle for carrying out direct investment in mining, " said the
paper.
</P>
<P>
The policy calls for " a well developed gemstone cutting and
jewellery industry making Tanzania the gemstone center for Africa
and providing dependable employment to Tanzanians," it added.
</P>
<P>
The policy will also ensure that contractual rights and
obligations are protected, and provide for settlement of disputes
through the courts or by international arbitration.
</P>
<P>
In implementing the policy, the Ministry of Energy and
Minerals will set up a Mining Board to supervise the mining
activities and stamp out illegal mining by issuing special
identification cards to all licensed small-scale miners, said the
report.
</P>
<P>
The World Bank has provided 13 million US dollars since 1995
for human resources and capacity building in the sector through
provision of technical assistance.
</P>
<P>
Currently Tanzania earns about 500 million US dollars annually
from exports which include minerals. Official sources said the
country's mineral sector is expected to attract up to 400 million
US dollars by the year 2,000. 
</P>
</TEXT>
