<HEADLINE> Rare Animal Bred in Beijing Zoo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 29 (Xinhua) -- One lester slow loris, a rare
primate under first-class state protection, has given birth to two
babies in the Beijing Zoo recently.
</P>
<P>
This is the first time the animal has been bred in the zoo.
</P>
<P>
Experts here say, it is difficult for the animal to reproduce
in northern China, for it is afraid of cold.
</P>
<P>
The lester slow loris, inhabiting in China's subtropical province
of Yunnan, was first found in 1986. The small, slow-moving
primate lives on trees and is active at night.
</P>
<P>
Since 1992, scientists in the Beijing Zoo have carried out
researches on the lester slow loris. They adjusted the
temperature, air humidity, and illumination in the animal's room
to imitate its living environment.
</P>
<P>
The two cubs will make a debut soon, said an official of the
zoo.
</P>
<P>
So far, more than 1,500 animals in over 100 species have been
bred in the zoo this year, including giant pandas, golden monkeys,
red-crowned cranes, swans and chimpanzees.  
</P>
</TEXT>
