<HEADLINE> 200 Rwandan Tutsi Flee to Uganda </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, December 29 (Xinhua) -- Over 200 Rwandan Tutsi
refugees have fled to south-western Uganda, local media reported
today.
</P>
<P>
About 220 Tutsi are now camping in Bunagana, Kisoro District,
to wait for a registration, said Abdullah Kiganda, the district's
Chief Administrative Officer.
</P>
<P>
They entered Uganda in the wake of vicious attacks by
extremist Hutu militants in Rwanda early last week, the officer
added.
</P>
<P>
Local authorities are trying to settle the refugees in
Nyakibonde Camp sponsored by United Nations' High Commission for
Refugees, the officer said.
</P>
<P>
Sagahutu Murahsi, the Rwandan ambassador to Uganda, told the
"The Monitor" yesterday that his country is trying to avoid
escalation of tribal killings by all means. He admitted that the
violence of Hutu extremists is responsible for the new exodus of
Tutsi people.
</P>
<P>
The Rwandan government troops have entered the areas of
Ruhengeri and Gisenyi, where violence had happened, to secure the
local situation, the ambassador said. 
