<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Brief Notes on Major Kenyan Presidential </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, December 29 (Xinhua) -- Following are the brief
introduction of eight out of 15 presidential candidates in
Kenya's second multi-party elections held today.
</P>
<P>
Daniel arap Moi -- 73 years old. Vice-President from 1969 to
1978 and President since 1978. Leader of the ruling Kenya African
National Union (KANU). Prominent peace-broker in the Great Lakes
region and eastern Africa. He is widely expected to win his final
five year term today mainly due to the division of the opposition
and his relatively most diluted tribal color. But issues like
allegedly rampant corruption, high unemployment and weak state of
infrastructure might lead him to a possible Waterloo. Coming from
Kalenjin, a minority community, he headed the 1992 poll with 36.8
percent of the vote.
</P>
<P>
Mwai Kibaki -- 66 years old. KANU's National Executive Officer
in early 1960s, cabinet minister from 1964 to 1978, Vice-
President from 1978 to 1988 and Chairman of the opposition
Democratic Party (DP) since 1992. He is seen as the most serious
challenger to Moi in today's poll and believed to get a majority
in Central Province. A member of Kikuyu, the largest tribe making
up about 25 percent of Kenya's population, he took the third
place in the 1992 race with 19.45 percent of the vote.
</P>
<P>
Charity Ngilu -- 45 years old. One of the first two women ever
to vie for the top seat in Kenya and, if successful, she would be
sub-Saharan Africa's first elected female president. As many
people believe, she stands a real chance in today's voting mainly
due to her clarion call for social changes and fresh image
untainted by scandals. She was one of the rare rags-to-riches
women in Africa and first walked into politics in 1992 when
elected to parliament for the DP which she quit this year so as
to run on the Social Democratic Party (SDP) ticket. She comes
from Kamba tribe.
</P>
<P>
Michael Kijana Wamalwa -- 53 years old. Official leader of the
opposition in the just-dissolved seventh parliament and Chairman
of FORD-Kenya which is the only party in the country with a
parliamentary representative in each province. Once lecturer in
law at Nairobi University, he first won the parliamentary seat in
1979 and became the second vice chairman of FORD in September
1992 soon before FORD split into FORD-Kenya and FORD-Asili. He
gets support mainly from his own Luhya tribe, the third largest
in the country.
</P>
<P>
Raila Odinga -- 52 years old. Leader of the opposition
National Democratic Party (NDP). Second son of Kenya's first Vice-
President Jaramogi Oginga Odinga who was widely respected by
Kenyans as a nationalist hero. He got a degree in mechanical
engineering in Democratic Germany in 1970, has been detained three
times by the Moi government and was elected Vice-Chairman of
FORD in 1992. He quit FORD-Kenya to join SDP in January. A
prominent role in opposition campaigns mid this year for pressing
the government to conduct minimum constitutional reforms before
elections, he commands broad support in western Kenya, especially
among young people from his Luo tribe, the second largest in the
country.
</P>
<P>
Koigi wa Wamwere -- 49 years old. Leader of Kenya National
Democratic Alliance (KENDA). He served in parliament as a KANU
dissident in the one-party era, detained without trial or charge
for three years under late President Jomo Kenyatta's rule. After
several years in exile in Norway, he was re-arrested in 1990 and
spent another two years in jail charged with treason. The charge
was finally dropped without explanation. In 1995 he was sentenced
for four years for allegedly raiding a police station and
stealing guns. The judgement was nullified by the Supreme Court
on the first day of this month, making him eligible to run at the
last minute. He is said enormously popular among peasant farmers,
both among his own Kikuyu and other ethnic groups.
</P>
<P>
Martin Shikuku -- A Kikuyu, 62 years old. Leader of the opposition
FORD-Asili and the party's parliamentary member. He is one of the
few pre-independence politicians still in politics. Elected in
parliament in 1963. Detained in 1975 for saying KANU was "dead"
and released in 1978. Served as an assistant minister between
1980 and 1986 when he was dismissed after being accused by Moi of
making disparaging remarks about Kenyatta and his government. In
1992, he became the Secretary-General of FORD, but soon fell out
with Oginga Odinga. When the party split, he joined FORD-Asili
and Odinga formed FORD-Kenya.
</P>
<P>
George Anyona -- 52 years old. Leader and the sole
parliamentary member of the Kenya Social Congress party. A former
university lecturer and political prisoner, he was first elected
to parliament in 1974. He was the secretary of the Inter-Parties
Parliamentary Group which drew up constitutional revisions
enacted before parliament was dissolved last month. A Kisii from
western Nyanza province, he garnered less than one percent of the
vote in the 1992 elections.
</P>
<P>
Other seven candidates, representing minor parties,
are Madam Wangari Maathai of Liberal Party, Kimani wa Nyoike of
FORD-People, Munyua Waiyaki of Patriotic Party of Kenya (UPPK),
Katama Mkangi of Kenya National Congress, Waweru Ng'ethe of Umma
Party, Godfrey Mwireria of Green African Party and Stephen
Wilfred Omondi Oludhe of Economic Independence Party, who
announced his quit yesterday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
