<HEADLINE> Thailand to Review Nuclear Reactor Plan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, December 29 (Xinhua) -- Thai Prime Minister Chuan
Leekpai has ordered to review the country's plan to build a
nuclear research reactor amid worries over safety problems, The
Bangkok Post reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
Chuan gave the order as the planned project to build a 10
megawatt reactor in Ongkharak district of Nakhon Nayok province
received no safety license, the newspaper said.
</P>
<P>
The Nuclear Safety Subcommittee did not grant a safety license
to the project, the site work of which had already started with
U.S. nuclear reactor builder General Atomics commissioned to build
and operate the facility, the newspaper said.
</P>
<P>
The deal for the 3.8-billion-baht (84.4 million U.S. dollar
under the exchange rate when the contract was signed) project was
approved on June 1 this year by the then Chavalit Yongchaiyudh
government, which reportedly bypassed the subcommittee chaired by
the permanent secretary of Thailand's Science, Technology and
Environment Ministry.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. Nuclear Regulatory Commission refused to conduct a
safety review of the Thai reactor according to the terms of
references on the project on grounds that the planned reactor was
a mix of U.S. and Australian technology, the newspaper quoted a
government source as saying.
</P>
<P>
General Atomics has already started preparing the land for the
reactor, the source said, adding that if the government now
decides to scrape the project, it will face a loss of a down
payment of 300 million baht (6.67 million dollars).  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
