<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thai Government to Probe Central Bank's Mismanagement </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, December 29 (Xinhua) -- Thai Prime Minister Chuan
Leekpai has promised that his government will clean up the central
bank and punish those found guilty of mismanagement.
</P>
<P>
In an exclusive interview with the Bangkok Post published on
Monday, the prime minister said the government would make it a
priority to examine the Bank of Thailand's role in implementing
economic measures over the past few years.
</P>
<P>
Chuan said the probe will review the granting of a 100-billion
baht (4 billion U.S. dollar then) loan to the Bangkok Bank of
Commerce (BBC), which ran into severe financial problems two years
ago after allegedly over-extending loans to businesses and people
closely connected to the bank's executives on over-valued
collaterals.
</P>
<P>
Investigations will also be carried out into the fast depletion
of Thailand's foreign reserves, which were used to defend
belatedly the Thai currency against currency speculators, and the
use of huge sums, estimated at more than 430 billion baht (16.86
billion dollars then), of the country's development fund to prop
up ailing private finance firms.
</P>
<P>
Of 58 such firms suspended by the government in June and August
this year, 56 have been closed down.
</P>
<P>
In the last few months, some academics and financial analysts
have held the central bank partly responsible for the country's
financial crisis.
</P>
<P>
An investigation led by Suthee Singhasaneh, former finance
minister, found abuse of authority and blunders made at the
highest levels of the central bank, the report said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
