<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Foreign Investment in Myanmar Reaches 6.5 Billion US </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANGON, December 29 (Xinhua) -- Foreign investment in Myanmar
increased by 1.18 billion U.S. dollars in the first 11 months of
this year, bringing the total foreign investment to 6.53 billion
dollars at the end of November, the latest official statistics
show.
</P>
<P>
The increase, however, was less than that in the corresponding
period of last year, which was 2.18 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
Of the 23 countries and regions which invest in the country,
Britain, Singapore, Thailand, the United States and Malaysia are
leading with 1.32 billion, 1.30 billion, 1.15 billion, 582 million
and 524 million dollars respectively.
</P>
<P>
Of the total foreign investment in Myanmar, other five ASEAN
(Association of Southeast Asian Nations) countries -- Singapore,
Thailand, Malaysia, Indonesia and the Philippines -- shared 45
percent, investing more than 3 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
The 10 foreign-invested sectors involving 289 permitted
projects are oil and gas, manufacturing, real estate, hotels and
tourism, mining, transport and communications, livestock and
fisheries, industrial estate, construction and agriculture.
</P>
<P>
Myanmar began to shift its centrally-planned economic system
towards a market-oriented one when the country opened its door to
the outside world in late 1988.  
</P>
</TEXT>
