<HEADLINE> Turbulence on U.S. Flight Kills One, Injures Many </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, December 29 (Xinhua) -- One passenger was killed and 63
people were injured as a U.S. passenger plane en route from Tokyo to
Hawaii was buffeted by heavy turbulence on Sunday, reports here
said.
</P>
<P>
The accident occurred when the Boeing 747 jumbo jet, which
departed Narita, Japan, at 9:05 p.m. local time (1205 GMT), was
ascending at an altitude of 9,400 meters over the Pacific Ocean.
</P>
<P>
The reports said the turbulence was so violent that passengers
and flight attendants were thrown against the overhead luggage
compartments and the ceiling.
</P>
<P>
The seat belt sign was not turned on because the turbulence was
totally unexpected.
</P>
<P>
The injured were rushed to hospitals after the United Airline
flight returned to Tokyo's Narita airport, said Donna Sitkiewicz,
director of communications for the airline.
</P>
<P>
A 32-year-old woman died after being taken to a hospital near
the airport, officials said.
</P>
<P>
Sitkiewicz said the poor flying conditions had not shown up on
the plane's radar system.
</P>
<P>
The flight was carrying 393 passengers and 19 crew members.
</P>
<P>
The Officials said the incident would be investigated by the U.S.
National Transportation Safety Board because it involved an
American plane and occurred over international waters. 
</P>
</TEXT>
