<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippines' Economy to Grow 4 percent in 1998: ADB </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, December 29 (Xinhua) -- The Asian Development Bank
(ADB) expects the Philippine economy to slow down next year to
4-4.5 percent in terms of gross national product (GNP) growth rate
due to the current financial problem, local press reports said
Monday.
</P>
<P>
The reports said this projection is in line with the
government's outlook for 1998, which was revised down almost three
percentage points from the original target to 4.5 percent for GNP
and 4 percent for gross domestic product (GDP), in anticipation of
the twin effects of the financial turmoil in the region and the El
Nino phenomenon.
</P>
<P>
However, the ADB said keeping growth prospects at this level
will require extra care from the government to ease interest rates
to more normal levels and moderate public investments to
accommodate increased external debt-servicing obligations and thus
remove pressure on the fiscal balance.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the bank said the Philippines' inflation will be a
main problem next year, being sensitive to both movements of the
peso and weather changes.
</P>
<P>
The ADB expected the inflation rate to shoot up to 10 percent
next year, much higher than the government-planned 6.5-7.5
percent. The rate remained at an averaged low level of 5 percent
in the first 11 months of this year.
</P>
<P>
The bank added that the upward adjustments of interest rates
after the peso was floated in July "could aggravate the financial
position of the corporate sector, worsen the investment climate in
the economy, choke economic growth and prolong the economic
slowdown."
</P>
<P>
"It would be more appropriate for the government to reduce
interest rates to more normal levels and leave the nominal
exchange rate to the foreign exchange market. Lowering the
interest rates should take precedence over stabilizing the
exchange rate," the ADB said.
</P>
<P>
The bank, however, noted that if the currency adjustment is
managed efficiently and if political stability follows the
presidential polls in May next year, growth could resume after
1998 to signal the end of the stormy aftershocks of the regional
currency malaise.
</P>
<P>
"Over the long term, the Philippine economy should come out
stronger from the current currency adjustment," it said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
