<HEADLINE> More Wild Animals Inhabit Changbai Mountains in NE China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHANGCHUN, December 29 (Xinhua) -- Large numbers of black
bears, wild boars and roe deers are being frequently spotted in the
Changbai Mountains in northeast China's Jilin Province, due to
the hunting ban implemented two years.
</P>
<P>
Ren Junjie, vice-chairman of the Standing Committee of the
Jilin provincial people's congress, said the sightings were
reported by an inspection group that has just completed its tour of
Jilin, Tonghua and Baishan cities and the Yanbian Korean
Autonomous Prefecture.
</P>
<P>
Ren said illegal hunting has been greatly reduced since the
province's five-year ban became effective in January of 1996.
</P>
<P>
In addition, expanding forests in the mountainous areas and
increased knowledge of wild-animal protection have contributed to
the improvement of natural habitats and increases in the animal
population.
</P>
<P>
Jilin is the country's only region that has enforceed a hunting
ban throughout the province.
</P>
<P>
In Tonghua's rural areas, residents once discovered 26 roe deers
in a group and several hundreds of wild ducks flying to a river
on the outskirts of the city.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, the swan geese, which had disappeared in the
city for many years, has returned to Jilin this year.
</P>
<P>
Jilin has established a first-aid station for injured wild
animals and had rescued 21 wild animals three years after its
establishment.
</P>
<P>
Ren called for drafting a provincial regulation to compensate
those who are injured or whose property is damaged in protecting
the animals. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971229.0185 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Central Chinese Province Launches Survey of Wildlife Resources </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHANGSHA, December 29 (Xinhua) -- Central China's Hunan
Province has launched a survey of its wildlife resources to better
protect its natural habitats.
</P>
<P>
The survey will focus on animals, birds, amphibians, reptiles
and wild plants and wetland resources in more than 3,000 locations.
</P>
<P>
The forest coverage rate has exceeded 50 percent in the
province, and there are more than 600 kinds of terrestrial
animals, with 66 under state protection.
</P>
<P>
China launched the first-phase investigation of its wildlife
resources in 11 provinces in 1995. So far, the second-phase
investigation, including that in Hunan Province, is in full swing
throughout the country.
</P>
<P>
Experts pointed out that investigation of wild life resources
is significant in effectively protecting wildlife resources,
making concerned policies and implementing related international
conventions.
</P>
<P>
The overall survey is expected to be completed by 2000.
</P>
</TEXT>
