<HEADLINE> Anand, Adams Deadlocked after Third Draw </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GRONINGEN, December 28 (Xinhua) -- Viswanathan Anand and
Michael Adams drew their match for the third consecutive time in
their best-of-four World Chess Championship eliminator in
Groningen of the Netherlands on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Englishman Adams, playing white, opened with his king's pawn
and Anand of India countered with the Sicilian Defence.
</P>
<P>
Adams proposed a draw on move 35th. Games one and two were
drawn after 55 and 48 moves respectively.
</P>
<P>
If Monday's fourth game also ends in a draw, the contest will
be decided by a series of speed games.
</P>
<P>
The two grandmasters will then play two games with 25 minutes
thinking time each.
</P>
<P>
If that is still not enough to decide the winner, who will
challenge reigning world champion Anatoly Karpov of Russia, two
more games with 15 minutes each will be played.
</P>
<P>
A final "sudden death" blitz game will then be played in the
case that the two are still deadlocked.
</P>
<P>
The International Chess Federation (FIDE) title decider against
Karpov will be in a six-game format and begins in Lausanne,
Switzerland on January 1. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
