<DOCNO> XIE19971229.0193 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pak Foreign Secretary Holds Talks With Taliban Leaders </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, December 28 (Xinhua) -- Pakistan's Foreign Secretary
Shamshad Ahmad Saturday held detailed talks with Mulla Omar,
leader of the Afghan Islamic Taliban militia, on restoration of
peace in the war-torn Afghanistan, Associated Press of Pakistan
(APP) reported.
</P>
<P>
During the two-and-a-half hours meeting held in Kandahar,
Taliban's stronghold in southern Afghanistan, Shamshad highlighted
Prime Minister Nawaz Sharif's commitment to peace in Afghanistan,
according to APP.
</P>
<P>
Pakistan was convinced that durable peace in Afghanistan would
only be possible through negotiations, Shamshad said.
</P>
<P>
There was a need for all parties in Afghanistan to settle their
differences across the negotiating table rather than through
bloodshed, he said.
</P>
<P>
In this regard, Shamshad said, Pakistan fully supports the U.N.
peace efforts.
</P>
<P>
The foreign secretary also briefed Taliban leader Omar on
Sharif's recent meeting with a delegation of the anti-Taliban
northern alliance led by ousted Afghan president Burhanuddin
Rabbani.
</P>
<P>
Rabbani, who visited Pakistan earlier this week at the
invitation of Prime Minister Sharif, offered to hold peace talks
with the Taliban early next month.
</P>
<P>
Omar expressed his deep appreciation of Pakistan's efforts to
bring peace to Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
He reiterated their commitment to restoring durable peace in
Afghanistan in order to promote the peace process.
</P>
<P>
The Taliban leader proposed a meeting of Ulema representing the
student militia and those opposed to them to discuss how to reach
a peaceful settlement of the country's ongoing conflict.
</P>
<P>
He said the proposed meeting may be held in Islamabad or any
other place agreed upon on mutually convenient dates.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
