<DOCNO> XIE19971229.0194 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-28 21:15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Suez Canal Tolls Not to Be Changed in 1998 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, December 28 (Xinhua) -- Chairman of Egypt's Suez Canal
Authority (SCA) Ahmed Ali Fadel announced today that the tolls of
ships sailing through the international waterway will not be
changed in 1998.
</P>
<P>
The decision came despite continuing drops in SCA's revenues,
Fadel said at a press conference held in Ismailia midway of the
canal and about 120 kilometers east of the capital.
</P>
<P>
He said that the economic unit of the SCA has recommended the
tolls which have been in place since 1994 be kept intact.
</P>
<P>
Discounts will continue to be given to tankers from the Gulf,
ships and tankers from Australia to the Mediterranean ports, from
Japan to Europe and from the United States to the Gulf, he said.
</P>
<P>
The discounts range from 5 to 35 percent according to various
factors including the types and loads of the ships, and whether
they are on a one way or round trip basis.
</P>
<P>
Studies are underway on a Qatari request for further toll
reduction for liquefied natural gas carriers from the Gulf country
and an agreement will be reached and applied, Fadel said.
</P>
<P>
He disclosed that the revenues of the Suez Canal, the third
largest foreign-currency earner in Egypt, in 1997 stand at 1.822
billion U.S. dollars, down by 3 percent compared to 1996.
</P>
<P>
A 5.7 percent devaluation of the Special Drawing Rights of the
International Monetary Fund also ate into the the earnings, but he
said that is "acceptable."
</P>
<P>
The 193-kilometer canal, which stretches from Port Said in the
north to the town of Suez in the south, is the longest lock-free
canal in the world.
</P>
<P>
The canal linking the Mediterranean and the Red Sea was opened
on November 17, 1879 and was nationalized by Egypt on July 26,
1956. 
</P>
</TEXT>
